<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Minister on Fight Against Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Minister for Home
Affairs Wong Kan Seng declared the National Anti-Drug Abuse
Campaign '96 open here today and said Singapore is on the right
path, but the fight against drug abuse is far from over.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will not hesitate to introduce deterrent
measures and stiffer penalties, citing the example of the ecstasy
drug, which is fast making its way into night-spots in this tiny
island republic.
</P>
<P>
"The ecstasy pills phenomenon illustrates the fluid nature of
the drug situation and the reason why we must never let our guard
down," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the combined efforts of the government and community
groups, he said, the number of new addicts in 1995 had decreased,
the upward trend in the proportion of Malay addicts in the Drug
Rehabilitation Centers had halted, and the number of first-timer
Malay addicts as well as local new addicts had fallen.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the right path but the fight against drug abuse is
far from over," he stressed, pointing out that new drugs and new
trends and development could suddenly appear and become a problem
overnight.
</P>
<P>
This year's campaign aims at getting through the important
message that drug abuse can cause permanent damage to a person's
brain and body, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the responsibility of preventing drug
addictions and protecting the youths from drugs does not rest
solely on the government and community groups. Parents have a big
role to play in this important duty to protect the youths, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
