<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study:U.S. Economy Can Go Up Without Runaway Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economic development
can be put at a much quicker pace without runaway of inflation, a
major manufacturing trade group said today.
</P>
<P>
The view is included in a study released by the National
Association of Manufacturers in the country.
</P>
<P>
Non-inflationary, higher growth is possible due to
technological advances and structurally lower inflation possible
due to increased international competition and domestic
deregulation, said Jasinowski, president of the manufacturers
group and author of the study.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth can be boosted from the current 2.2 percent
to 3 percent by the year 2000 without rising of inflation, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
The study named "The Case for Higher Growth" notes many
economists including those at the Federal Reserve and on Wall
Street generally believe the economy can grow no more than 2.3
percent annually without overheating.
</P>
<P>
Jasinowski said the conventional view that the higher growth
will result in higher inflation is wrong. "This view does not take
into account changes that are creating a new economy," he said.
"As a result of technological advances and greater capital
investment, the growth rate could rise to 2.8 percent."
</P>
<P>
He urged the nation to set an interim goal of 3 percent growth
by the year 2000 and to "explore the types of long-term structural
changes that can eventually achieve a growth rate approaching 3.5
percent."
</P>
<P>
Jasinowski said economic growth has averaged 3.2 percent since
the 1870s and exceeded 5 percent annually in the 1960s. By
comparison, growth has averaged only 2.2 percent a year in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
To reach 3 percent, he contends, monetary policy must be
loosened to permit lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Several policy changes also will be needed, including a
balanced budget, a smaller trade deficit, tax policy revisions to
increase both investment and worker productivity and government
regulatory reforms to reduce the costs of business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
