<HEADLINE> Mugabe in Accra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
left for Accra, Ghana, today to attend an international
conference on reviving private investment in Africa, according a
report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference which began on Monday will discuss
investment on the continent and how foreign investors can be
attracted to Africa.
</P>
<P>
The government of Ghana and the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa are organizing the conference.
</P>
<P>
Selected African leaders and prominent business leaders will
hold a summit round table, one of the key events at the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference will delve into four potential investment
sectors: infrastructure, telecommunications, financial services
and agri-business.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe will be one of the selected countries to meet with
potential investors and outline its investment policies and
market opportunities. 
</P>
