<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting in Mogadishu Spreads to City center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The forces of the two main
warlords in Mogadishu General Mohamed Farah Aidid and Ali Mahdi
Mohamed engaged in bitter fighting today at the Green Line
dividing the war-torn capital.
</P>
<P>
At least seven people have been killed and as many as 14
others wounded in the fighting at the heart of the city today.
</P>
<P>
The fighting is said to have started when militiamen loyal to
Ali Mahdi Mohamed were deployed along the Green Line last night
in an effort to weaken the militia strength of Aidid against Ali
Mahdi's ally Osman Hassan Ali Atto in South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people have been fleeing their houses with a
little belongings in the districts of Bondhere, Wardhighley and
Shingani to the relatively safe areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
Some told reporters that they had left their houses which they
refurbished along the Green Line just after the end of the
disastrous fighting between these two warlords in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The clashes at the Green Line followed when the militiamen of
Aidid retook control of the strategic point of K-7 from the hands
of Atto's militiamen last night.
</P>
<P>
The junction which links Mogadishu to the southern regions of
Somalia fell to Atto two days ago.
</P>
<P>
The fighting which ensued between forces of Atto and Aidid
over the control of the junction has claimed the lives of more
than 13 people while the wounded exceeded 19 in heavy fighting
last night.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi, the North Mogadishu faction leader, seems to be
fully and practically supporting Atto and his Abgal clansmen
living in Medina district of South Mogadishu neighboring Bosnia
vicinity where Atto found his base.
</P>
<P>
The involvement of Ali Mahdi in this new round of fighting may
turn the motive of the armed challenges in Mogadishu into a clan
war between the Habar Gidir clan of General Aidid and Abgal clan
of Ali Mahdi.
</P>
<P>
This is also likely to unite the militiamen of Osman Atto and
General Aidid, thus further complicating any lasting solution to
Somalia's multi-politicized crisis.
</P>
<P>
Casualty figures included more than 50 fatalities and nearly a
hundred others wounded and they were mainly civilians hit by
stray rounds of mortars and heavy machine gun bullets since the
fighting broke out in South Mogadishu last Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
