<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Gov't Accepts Business Community's Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government today
accepted the major demands of the business community for the next
fiscal budget, said President of Federation of Pakistan Chambers
of Commerce and Industry (FPCCI) Ilyas Bilour.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here on the conclusion of a
three-day intensive talks between the government and the FPCCI,
Bilour said that most of their demands would be later incorporated
in the money bill.
</P>
<P>
Expressing gratitude to the government, he said the talks were
held in a congenial and affable atmosphere and cooperation between
the government and the business community would continue in
future.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen after the meeting, Asif Ali Zardari, head of
the government negotiating team, said that the talks were held in
a very amiable and cordial manner and there was a spirit of
cooperation with each other on both sides.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The business community cooperated with us and we will
continue to work together."
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government this month announced the budget for
the fiscal year of July 1996 to June 1997, imposing the heaviest
tax in the country's history, which drew protest from the business
community.
</P>
<P>
The opposition called a countrywide strike against the budget
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, the FPCCI decided not to participate in the strike and
accepted the government's invitation for talks on the budget.
</P>
<P>
The main demands of the FPCCI presented to the government
included exemption of one house and one ship from wealth tax,
continuation of fixed sales tax scheme on 28 industries, reduction
in the rate of general sales tax and other issues concerning sales
tax and income tax and removal of anomalies in customs and
exercise duty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
