<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Wildlife Policy Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has one of the most
successful community controlled wildlife programs in Africa, a
prominent conservationist said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Pan-African Symposium on Natural Resources
Management, the Southern African Sustainable Use Specialist Group
Chairman Rowan Martin said wildlife management under the communal
areas management program for indigenous resources (CAMPFIRE) is
playing its rightful role in land use and the economy of
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"This is a grassroots movement which empowers rural people to
undertake their own wildlife management and to receive direct
benefits from it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Martin told the 100 delegates from 20 African countries that
more than five percent of Zimbabwe's 10.5 million people are now
involved in CAMPFIRE.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, he said, had a strong commitment to enhance rural
prosperity and considered that both the conservation and the use
of its natural resources could be harmonized to achieve
sustainable development for all its people.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe's policy is to encourage the sustainable use of
wildlife and its habitat, recognizing that this is only likely if
wildlife can be used profitably, the primary benefits accruing to
people with wildlife on their land," said Martin.
</P>
<P>
The delegates from English- and French-speaking Africa are
exchanging experience on natural resource management in the
symposium which started on Monday and will end on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Condemns Saudi Bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain today seriously condemned a
bomb attack Tuesday night on a military complex in Saudi Arabia,
extending its sympathies to the families of the victims and
offering its assistance to help bring those responsible to
justice.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC television, Prime Minister John Major
condemned the attack as "appalling act, an act of pure evil".
</P>
<P>
"A large number of innocent people were just brutally murdered.
I very much hope that we very soon find out who did it so they can
be punished," Major said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind said in a statement that "the
British government condemns in the strongest possible terms the
appalling terrorist attack in Saudi Arabia last night."
</P>
<P>
"We extend our sympathies to the families of the victims. We
will give maximum assistance to Saudi Arabia in its efforts to
identify the perpetrators," Rifkind added.
</P>
<P>
At least 23 Americans have been reportedly killed and over 300
wounded in a bomb attack on an air base Tuesday night in the Saudi
city of Khobar.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 British Royal Air Force personnel are stationed in
Khobar as part of a multinational operation to enforce a no-fly
zone imposed by the United Nations over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
But Rifkind said that he was not aware of any British
casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
