<HEADLINE> SADC Officials Discuss Regional Matters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Immigration and police
ministers of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
will open three-day talks today in Gaborone on combating drug
trafficking in the region and free movement of its peoples.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the meeting is to discuss
draft protocols on the issues and will precede a heads of state
meeting on Friday of the 12-member organization.
</P>
<P>
The leaders at Friday's summit will launch the SADC's new
body, "the security organ", on politics, defense and security and
possibly discuss the mounting political tension in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The SADC secretariat said in a statement the body would
provide the framework through which member countries would
coordinate their efforts.
</P>
<P>
"The SADC leaders will also review developments in the region
and internationally, with particular emphasis on matters relating
to politics, defense and security in southern Africa," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
SADC information officer Kgosinkwe Moesi said today the
"security organ" would effectively combine the activities of the
proposed sector for conflict resolution and management, the
proposed association of southern African states and the Frontline
states.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member SADC comprises Angola, Botswana, Lesotho,
Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
