<HEADLINE> New US Ambassador to Zambia Nominated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
nominated a woman career diplomat named Arlene Rebder as new
ambassador to Zambia to replace Roland Kuchel.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of Render, currently in charge of Central
African affairs, will become effective after the U.S. Senate
confirms her nomination, a news release from the American center
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Render said if she is confirmed she will work energetically to
advance the United States interests in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Render who has 26 years of foreign affairs said she will use
the experience to encourage Zambia in its transition period to
the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
However, Render said that the recent actions by the Zambian
government threaten to damage the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
After Zambian President Frederick Chiluba signed a
constitution amendment bill into law at the end of last month the
U.S. administration threatened to withhold its aid to Zambia
unless the later backs down on the bill, which bars former
president Kenneth Kaunda from standing in the general elections
because Kaunda's parents were Malawian immigrants. 
</P>
