<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Releases Tourism White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The South African tourism
industry has the potential for significant growth on job
creation, said the tourism white paper released in Pretoria
today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement after the release of the white paper, the
Environmental Affairs and Tourism Department said tourism, which
at present contributes four percent to the gross domestic product
(GDP), has the potential to increase to eight percent of the GDP
by 2000 and to 10 percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
In monetary terms, this will represent an increase in foreign
exchange earnings from the present 10 billion Rand (about 2.32
billion US Dollars) to 9.3 billion US Dollars, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that one million or more jobs can be created
directly and indirectly should such growth be achieved.
</P>
<P>
However, constraints on growth mentioned in the white paper
include inadequate resourcing and funding of the industry,
inadequate training of locals to improve service levels and
supply the industry's labor needs, absence of sound environmental
management and lack of infrastructure, particularly in the rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said the white paper's departure point is
the sustainable development of tourism as a national priority in
a way which will significantly improve the quality of life of all
South Africans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the white paper proposed some specific guidelines
for implementation, such as a special tourism safety and security
program, improved access to funding through government channels
and aggressive local and international marketing program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
