<HEADLINE> Striking Swazi Teachers to Discuss Court Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Teachers and civil servants
in Swaziland are meeting today to discuss what action to take
after the country's Industrial Court ordered them to end their
strike action.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Mbabane said the 10,000-strong Swaziland National
Association of Teachers (SNAT) has called a mass meeting to be
held tomorrow in Manzini.
</P>
<P>
SNAT Secretary-General Saladin Magagula said today the
association's next course of action would be decided at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Association of Civil Servants (ACS) of
Swaziland will also be meeting in Manzini to discuss the court
order.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial Court claims both organizations have violated
their collective agreements with the Swazi government.
</P>
<P>
The teachers and civil servants went on a 10-day strike to
demand an 18 percent salary increase. The Swazi government is
offering them 9.9 percent plus a four percent increase in
allowances.
</P>
<P>
After the court's finding, Swazi Education Minister Solomon
Dlamini on Monday night announced schools would reopen.
</P>
<P>
Most schools in and around Mbabane were yesterday functioning
normally but teachers at some schools in the capital and Manzini
sent pupils home.
</P>
<P>
The strike decision taken by the ACS executive received poor
support and had little impact on the civil service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
