<HEADLINE> Andreas Papandreou Laid to Rest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Former Greek Premier and President
of the ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) Andreas
Papandreou was buried today in Athens first cemetery with full
state honours, after lying in state at the the Athens Cathedral
for the past three days.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou died early on Sunday of heart attack at his suburban
Athens home. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou's funeral started at 2:30 in the afternoon with a
service at the Athens Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the congregation, Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis said "PASOK has lost its founder and creator and we have
lost the man who inspired us with his ideas".
</P>
<P>
"Papandreou went against the current, demanding the
regeneration of the political system, expressing the centre-left
for 35 years and marking the beginning of a new period in our
political life and the progressive front," Simitis said, adding
that Papandreou "Leaves us his passion for life, his
forward-looking views, his courage and determination for freedom,
social sensitivity and justice.
</P>
<P>
After the service and tribute, Papandreou's coffin was placed
on a gun-carriage as guards of honour from the three services
presented arms.
</P>
<P>
The carriage was accompanied by long-time political associates
and friends of Papandreou holding black funeral ribbons, followed
immediately by members of his family and subsequently, Greek
President Kostis Stephanopoulos, Premier Simitis, Parliament
Speaker Apostolos Kaklamanis, opposition party leaders, ministers,
and the foreign dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
The funeral procession made the first stop outside the
parliament where there was a 21-gun salute. eight war planes
flew-past the procession.
</P>
<P>
An enormous crows of people from all corners of Greece joined
the funeral procession, following the carriage as it made its way
through central Athens to Papandreou's last resting place at the
first cemetery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
