<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Offers Reward for Capturing Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has offered a
reward of 366,000 Riyals (nearly 100,000 U.S. dollars) for
capturing the criminals who detonated the bomb Tuesday night in
the country's eastern city of Dhahran, which killed at least 19
Americans.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Saudi Interior Ministry announced today
the sum of money was earmarked for whomever provides information
that can lead to the arrest of those who masterminded and
perpetrated the crime.
</P>
<P>
A strong truck explosion occurred at a U.S. military housing
complex belonging to the Saudi Defense and Aviation Ministry in
the city. The eight-storied building housing 2,900 American
soldiers as well as some French and British personnel were almost
destroyed as a crater 11 meters deep ad 26 meters wide on the
street just outside the housing compound was blasted.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Interior Ministry statement said the death toll in
the explosion rose to 19 and the injured number increased to 386.
</P>
<P>
Among the wounded, there are 105 Americans, 47 Saudis, 118
Bangladeshis, four Egyptians, two Jordanians and two Indonesians.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged citizens and expatriates to cooperate with
the Saudi authorities in arresting the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
So far still no one has claimed responsibility for the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
The blast was the second attack targeting Americans in the
kingdom in seven months. Last November, a U.S. military
installation was attacked in another car bomb blast which killed
five Americans and two Indians.
</P>
<P>
Four Saudi nationals convicted of the crime were beheaded
at the end of May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
