<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-26 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Makes Contacts on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Secretary-General's
special envoy for Cyprus, Han Sung-Joo, started making contacts
with leaders of both the Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot
communities on the island to get himself acquainted with the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Han, who arrived in Cyprus Tuesday, had an hour-long meeting
with President Glafcos Clerides soon after his arrival.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Han said he had "a very good and
constructive discussion" with President Clerides, whom he met for
the second time.
</P>
<P>
The two men first met in Geneva on June 11, but he said this
time they had "a much more in-depth discussion of the issues and
possibilities."
</P>
<P>
Han also said he will try two approaches for solving the
Cyprus problem, that is, he will work for "incremental
improvement" and "quantum jump."
</P>
<P>
Today, he met with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in the
Turkish-controlled northern part of Nicosia, only divided capital
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Denktash is reported to have asked the U.N. envoy to talk
President Clerides into accepting a dialogue to establish if
there is common ground to start talks between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.N. envoy's contacts on the island,
government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides said here today that "I
believe the purpose of his visit here is to seek more views on how
to approach the Cyprus question."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said Han indicated that he intends to visit
European capitals and Washington in an effort to coordinate
efforts to make headway in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy, who is on a six-day visit to the island, is
scheduled to see President Clerides again Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and took control of the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
