<HEADLINE> Canada Condemns Bombing of Military Base in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien strongly condemned Tuesday's bombing of a military
compound in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, which houses American, British
French and Saudi military personnel and their families.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that some 20 people were killed, 240 injured,
over 100 of them seriously in the bombing. The majority of
casualties were American.
</P>
<P>
"This was the most heinous and cowardly act of terrorism," said
Chretien in a statement from his office today.
</P>
<P>
"Canada sincerely hopes that the responsible parties will be
apprehended quickly and brought to justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian prime minister, who is on a visit in Europe, also
extended deepest sympathy to the victims and their families.
</P>
<P>
Though more than 1,000 Canadians reside in the area, it appears
there were no Canadian casualties, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
No one yet has claimed responsibility to the bombing. 
</P>
