<HEADLINE> S.African Banks Lower Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Three major South African
banks today announced a one percent drop in their prime lending
rates and two of them said they would reduce their home loan
rates from July 1.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued in Johannesburg, First National
Bank and Nedcor, representing Nedbank and Permanent Bank, said
they would reduce home loan rates to 19.25 percent and prime
lending rates to 19.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
And, Standard Bank said it would reduce its prime lending rate
to 19.50 percent from July 1, while an announcement on home loan
rates would be made on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The announcements followed the decision by the Amalgamated
Banks of South Africa (ABSA) on Tuesday to reduce its prime
lending rate and home loan rate by one percentage point from July
1.
</P>
<P>
ABSA consists of United Bank, Trust Bank, Volkskas and Allied
Bank.
</P>
<P>
ABSA said the reduction had been made possible by the easing
''and an expectation of further softening'' of money market
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank Governor Chris Stals announced on Tuesday he was
prepared to ''lend some marginal support'' to the downward trend
in short-term money market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Stals said the Reserve Bank would also reduce the interest
rate for second-tier loans at the ''discount window'' from 1.5 to
0.75 percent from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nedcor Chief Executive Richard Laubscher said on Wednesday
Stals's reduction of the ''penalty rate'' was an additional
factor in making their decision.
</P>
<P>
The decision by the major banks to lower their prime lending
and home loan rates was welcomed by the Congress of South African
Trade Unions, saying this was a victory for all South Africans.
enditem

