<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Jiang on China's Peaceful Unification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an interview with the Spanish newspaper "El Pais (The Country),"
Jiang said: "I had declared that we welcome leaders of the Taiwan
authorities to visit the mainland in proper capacities and we are also
willing to accept the invitation of the Taiwan side and go to Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
"This principled stand of ours remain unchanged," said Jiang,
who arrived here Monday on a four-day state visit to Spain.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese President added that only so can the meeting between
leaders from both sides of the Taiwan strait bear substantive
meanings.
</P>
<P>
He said that opening negotiations for peaceful unification is
"our long-held position," adding that he proposed such negotiations
on behalf of the the Chinese Communist Party and the central
government on January 30, 1995.
</P>
<P>
"I proposed that as the first step, the two sides can hold
negotiations on officially ending hostilities under the principle of
one China and reach an agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
On this basis, he said, both sides commit themselves to defending
China's sovereignty and territorial integrity and making plans for
the development of their relations in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that Taiwan is an inalienable part of the Chinese
territory, and it is an entirely domestic affair of China to settle
the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
"We have insisted on solving the Taiwan issue in light of the
basic policy of peaceful unification and one country, two systems,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We don't commit ourselves to renouncing the use of force, which
is not directed against the Taiwan people, but against foreign
interventions and separatist attempts on the Taiwan island," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"We have to wait and see what the attitude of the Taiwan
authorities actually is," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
