<HEADLINE> S.Africa's Population Set for 21 Million Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's population is
expected to increase from the present 44.7 million to 65.7
million by the year 2020, according to a report released here
today.
</P>
<P>
The report, conducted by the Development Bank of Southern Africa,
was based on the results of official population censuses, other
secondary sources, and its own estimates based on statistical and
demographic techniques.
</P>
<P>
The expected increase would have a significant impact on the
delivery of public services and imfrastructure in urban
areas, the bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The report said, the population of Gauteng Province, South
Africa's economic powerhouse, is expected to double from the present
7.4 million to 14.7 million by 2020, increasing the province's
population density from 394 to 783 people per square metre.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, South Africa's population was 61.8 percent urbanised but
up to 82.4 percent could be expected to live in towns and cities by
2020.
</P>
<P>
''The implications of a national population increase of about 21
million over the next 25 years, coupled with increased population
density, are vast, particularly with regard to poverty, unemployment,
housing and the utilisation of natural resources,'' said the
statement. enditem

=06261955

=06261956
