<HEADLINE> 76 Foreign Companies Prospects for Gold in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-six foreign companies,
mostly from Canada, Britain, the United States, and South Africa,
are actively prospecting for gold in Ghana, Ghanaian President
Jerry Rawlings said today.
</P>
<P>
''Our annual production is over the one million ounces mark,''
said the president, quoted by a report reaching here today, in
addressing the International Conference on Reviving Private
Investment in Africa which is currently held in the Ghanaian
capital of Accra.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings said the Ashanti Goldfields Company, the largest in
Africa and the pride of Ghana, is itsself close to achieve the
one million ounce mark.
</P>
<P>
Ashanti has been able to attract large amounts of private capital
for its expansion activities in Ghana and other parts of Africa
because the company is listed in many stock exchanges around the
world.
</P>
<P>
''Such access to international capital markets is important for
the success of the private sector in Africa,'' said Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
The president also stated that efforts should be made to improve
energy supply in both west and southern Africa with the participation
of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
He emphasised the need to involve the private sector in the
implementation of projects such as the Nigeria gas supply to Benin,
Togo, Ghana, and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The Ghanaian president urged the African Development Bank,
and other regional and international financial institutions to be
actively involved in increasing private investment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference, which opened on Monday in Accra, is
being attended by over 1,000 participants from Africa, Europe, Asia
and the U.S.. 
</P>
</TEXT>
