<HEADLINE> Greek PM Threatens to Resign Unless Elected Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
threatened today to resign unless he is elected the new leader of
the ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK).
</P>
<P>
Simitis was addressing the party's fourth congress which opened
here a day after party leader and former prime minister Andreas
Papandreou was buried.
</P>
<P>
''Following the death of Andreas Papandreou, I am submitting my
candidacy for the post of party president,'' Simitis told the
congress attended by some 5,000 delegates.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said that if he was not elected, he would be compelled
to resign from the premiership.
</P>
<P>
He said his resignation would be necessary because "the prime
minister and the president of PASOK must be one and the same
person in order for the government to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
Simitis, who took over from the then-hospitalized Papandreou as
premier in January, faces stiff opposition from Akis
Tsohatzopoulos, a Papandreou confidant, who is certain to fight
for the party leadership.
</P>
<P>
The four-day congress is expected to elect a new leader on
Sunday. 
</P>
