<HEADLINE> Hardest Phase of Reform Over: Kazakhstan President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan must decide which
direction its economy should take now that the most difficult
phase had passed in its economic reform process, Kazakhstan's
President Nursultan Nazarbayev said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the national congress, Nazarbayev said that
major objectives in the reform program had been realized despite
mistakes and setbacks.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan will now speed up privatization and create favorable
conditions for foreign investment to bring the nation out of its
economic doldrums, he told more than 2,000 deputies.
</P>
<P>
He said that the monthly inflation rate in 1997 must be kept
below 1.5 percent and that annual inflation should not exceed 3.5
percent from 1997 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Kazakhstan's political system had taken
shape, the country had become a member of the international
community and the world had recognized Kazakhstan's independence.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan would pursue further economic reforms and would
ensure stability and harmony among the country's various
nationalities, he added. 
</P>
