<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Urges Action Against Financial Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji
said that corrupt people must be removed from the financial sector
and that financial crimes must be treated seriously.
</P>
<P>
"Financial criminal activities must be dealt with harshly so as
to guarantee the smooth working of our financial reforms and the
development of the finance industry," Zhu told a national meeting
on Wednesday, which was organized by the State Council and
attended by leading officials of banks and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
The financial community has made a great contribution to the
rapid and healthy development of the national economy over the
past several years, Zhu said, and it has also done well in
fighting corruption and in building clean and honest government.
</P>
<P>
Major economic crimes, fraud, robbery, and theft in the
financial sector have declined steadily over several years, Zhu
pointed out, noting that improved supervision has not only helped
maintain financial order but has improved economic order overall.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, financial crimes are a complex and
international social phenomenon and criminals will always target
banks.
</P>
<P>
"Fighting financial crimes is a long-term task and we must not
become slack now just because we have scored some success," Zhu
warned.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a serious amount of red-tape still exists in the
financial sector and the work against robbery, fraud and theft is
still not enough for public security.
</P>
<P>
There have been robberies of armored cars and of banking
businesses and bank employees have been killed, Zhu reminded those
attending.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the problem, he said, an effort must be made to
increase the struggle against corruption and financial crimes and
to rid the financial sector of embezzlers and corrupt people.
</P>
<P>
Financial security must also be improved and the installation
of electronic monitoring and alarm systems should be accelerated,
Zhu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
