<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Forecasts More Ocean Disasters This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China will have more and severe
oceanic natural disasters in 1996, with Zhejiang and Fujian
Provinces in east China more likely to take more of a lashing than
southern Guangdong Province, according to a press conference held
today by the National Bureau of Oceanography.
</P>
<P>
Four or five tidal storms caused by typhoons will hit coastal
areas of Zhejiang, Fujian, and southern China between now and
October. Several tidal storms are also predicted in the Bohai and
Laizhou bays.
</P>
<P>
The number of days with destructive waves, above four meters
high, will be more than last year's 278 days, and more will be
caused by tropical cyclones. Huge waves are quite likely to affect
parts of the Taiwan Straits and the East China Sea.
</P>
<P>
Eight or nine red tides will hit China's seashores this year,
almost the same number as last year. Most of them will occur on
seriously-contaminated seashores or in marine breeding areas.
</P>
<P>
But there will be no "el nino" phenomenon this year, which
refers to rapid rises of temperature in tropical areas of the
eastern pacific ocean, and tends to be followed by severe floods
or droughts in the following year in Asia and America.
</P>
<P>
There will be less sea ice in the Bouhai and northern Huanghai
seas from November 1996 to March 1997 than in the same period of
in the previous corresponding period, they said.
</P>
<P>
"The National Marine Environmental Forecasting Center has
intensified its monitoring efforts by reinforcing its work staff;
putting into operation various forecasting methods; checking its
facilities; and strengthening the consultation system," said Yu
Zhouwen, director of the National Marine Environmental Forecasting
Center.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid economic development of China's coastal areas
and the increasing density of population and assets, the annual
economic losses caused by the oceanic disasters have also risen
sharply, from about one billion yuan(114 million US dollars) in
early 1980s to about ten billion yuan(1.14 billion US dollars) in
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Fishing Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China will impose a fishing ban in
China's Yellow Sea and East China Sea from July 1 to August 31,
said an official with the Ministry of Agriculture today.
</P>
<P>
It follows the success of a similar ban in the area last year.
</P>
<P>
"No boat will be permitted to fish in July and August, and in
the following two months some limits will be exerted on fishing,"
said the official from the Department of Fishery under the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, boats can only fish in areas 30 sea
miles east of the fisheries-restriction line and a strict check
system of young fish proportions will be applied during the
September-October period.
</P>
<P>
Offshore fishing will be banned in the northern part of the
East China Sea and the southern part of Yellow Sea, covering
Zhejiang, Fujian, Jiangsu provinces and Shanghai Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Calling the "fishing ban" an effective way to protect China's
fish resources, especially the hairtail, the official said that
last year's fishing ban was a great success.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the country, for the first time, banned fishing in
July and August in its offshore fishing waters.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the autumn high water season in 1995,
the hairtail output increased by 14 percent over 1994, hitting a
record high.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the short-term fishing ban helped fishery companies
and fishermen reduce their costs, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The official admitted that there are still some problems
existing from last year's ban.
</P>
<P>
He noted that last year, though the country worked out limiting
regulations on fishery in September and October, the poor
administration impaired the whole process.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of fishery boats crowded within the fishery-banning
areas fishing young hairtail, offsetting the achievements gained
in the previous two months," said the official.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ministry this year will pay more attention to
the fishery management in the September-October period, while
sparing no efforts to do a good job in the July-August fishing
ban.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
