<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Have 120,000 Data Communication Network Users </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China will have 120,000 data
communication network users by the end of 1996, sources of the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications (MPT) said.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Yunjie, director of the Data Communication
Bureau under the MPT, China's data communication industry has
entered a stage of rapid development. China had only about 1,700
data communication users at the end of 1993, and the number has
climbed to about 100,000.
</P>
<P>
China adheres to the principle of seeking high starting points,
high levels and unconventional modes of development in the
construction of public data communication networks, Liu said, and
it has established a network system which provides a variety of
services and strong support for various information application
systems.
</P>
<P>
China has opened CHINAPAC, CHINADDN and CHINANET since 1993,
which have become the core of the country's information network.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, the networks had 31 major subscribers, and
many have built separate application systems by taking advantage
of the public data networks. They include institutions and
government departments, including national banks, the State
Commission of Economy and Trade, the State Administration of
Taxation, the Chinese Academy of Sciences, the State Education
Commission, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, China Travel Services, securities exchanges, futures
trade departments, public security departments, universities and
railway departments.
</P>
<P>
CHINAPAC currently covers more than 2,000 cities and has
100,000 ports. It is expected to reach more than 3,600 cities and
have 140,000 ports by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
CHINADDN listed users in more than 1,000 cities above the
county level at the end of 1995. It is expected to cover over
3,000 cities above the county level and have 140,000 ports by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
CHINANET now has subscribers in over 200 cities across the
country, and local networks are under construction.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate the number of public data network users in
China will reach one million by the end of 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
