<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disaster Relief Center Set Up in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A disaster relief center under
the Red Cross Society of China was set up today in Guangzhou,
capital city of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The eight-story center cost more than 11 million yuan (about
1.3 million US dollars) and will act as a comprehensive base for
the processing and storage of disaster relief materials, and
personnel training for Guangdong and southern China.
</P>
<P>
It was established with support from Red Cross societies in
China and the United States, as well as the Guangdong provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
Sun Baiqiu, vice president of the Red Cross Society of China,
said that the first disaster relief center was erected in Hangzhou
City six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the support of Red Cross societies in Japan, Germany, the
United States, Canada and Switzerland, similar centers have been
set up in Xiaogan, Shenyang and Chengdu cities, and a Xi'an center
will be completed later this year.
</P>
<P>
A disaster relief center in Tibet is already in use, and three
provincial centers in Anhui, Yunnan and Jiangsu provinces are
expected to go into operation by the end of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
