<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Unhappy with Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- African leaders in Ghana have
expressed disappointment at the low direct foreign investment in
the continent despite the adoption of investor-friendly policies
by most countries, a report from Accra said today.
</P>
<P>
At a roundtable summit which was part of the international
conference on reviving private investment in Africa on Wednesday
night, these leaders said they were seeking partnerships and not
aid from the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The summit, characterized by emotional pleas by presidents or
their representatives, brought to the fore Africa's shortcomings
in attracting investment.
</P>
<P>
Some leaders, including Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe,
were sceptical about how much economies should be opened up
without sacrificing national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"We are not asking for welfare," said host President Jerry
Rawlings, "because we have appropriate skills to do a lot of
things for ourselves."
</P>
<P>
Rawlings said privatizing crucial sectors such as
telecommunications could be retrogressive as most government
bills would be inflated.
</P>
<P>
"It is not everyone who goes into telecommunications for
economic reasons," agreed Mugabe. "some want to have their ears
everywhere," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe warned that some investors expected to control
economies and politics of countries in which they invested.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "we have to look at whether the role of
investment is for the development of economies or to extend
political control."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe and Rawlings emphasized that investment should be based
on partnership.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's first Vice-President Thabo Mbeki said developed
countries should show confidence in the continent's economies
first, for business people to be convinced there is a future in
investing in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the United Kingdom, the United States and
Malaysia said bureaucracy and rigid foreign currency regulations
should be scrapped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
