<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Issue Construction Licenses to Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will start issuing
licenses to foreign builders in November to allow them to
undertake civil engineering projects in the country, the
construction and transportation ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Two kinds of licenses will be issued: for general contractors
and for sub-contractors.
</P>
<P>
The ministry plans to issue the licensing regulations in July
and to begin accepting applications from foreign builders from
August 1.
</P>
<P>
Licenses will be issued only to foreign firms with at least one
year of experience in construction or to foreign individuals with
a minimum of 10-years experience with a construction firm and at
least two years of experience in supervisory positions.
</P>
<P>
Currently, construction companies in the country need no
experience to get a license for civil engineering projects while
individuals need at least 30 months of experience working for a
civil engineering firm.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is due to open its construction market on January
1, 1997. Foreigners will then be entitled to participate in open
bidding for public construction orders worth at least 6.2 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
They can also bid for similar orders from local governments or
state-subsidized firms worth more than 20.3 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
