<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Citizens Allowed to Mail Foreign Exchange Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China has opened the door for
citizens to send foreign exchange abroad.
</P>
<P>
Beginning July 1, Chinese people with valid visas who are
leaving the country will be allowed to bring or remit foreign
exchange abroad, according to regulations revealed by the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange.
</P>
<P>
To buy medicine, instruments and books, or to pay registration
fees, tuition and living expenses, people can mail foreign
exchange abroad after presenting the appropriate admission letters
or receipts.
</P>
<P>
When parents, spouses or children living abroad die, become
seriously ill, or face unexpected disasters, people can send
foreign exchange to them from China, but they must have in hand
valid certificates, reports or prescriptions issued by foreign
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Banks will determine whether depositors can remit abroad
foreign exchange valued at less than 2,000 US dollars. And the
local foreign exchange administration decides when between
2,000-5,000 US dollars can be sent to other countries.
</P>
<P>
Approval from the state foreign exchange administration is
necessary for people to send more than 5,000 US dollars to other
countries or regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
