<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Repatriates 244 Vietnamese Boat People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Some 244 Vietnamese boat people
returned to their home country Wednesday aboard the Indonesian
navy warship Kri Teluk Hading, according to reports reaching here
this evening from Batam, Riau province.
</P>
<P>
They were the first batch of refugees in Galang island, Riau
province, West Sumatra, to be repatriated under the orderly return
program (ORP) implemented by the Galang '96 humanitarian task
force, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government decided to repatriate Vietnamese
refugees following a decision of the United Nations to stop
financial aid to the boat people staying on Galang island.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
decided at the end of May to stop its aid till May 31, and all the
repatriation expenses will be borne by the UN agency.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, which for the past 20 years has been sheltering
refugees in Galang island, is under pressure from the UNHCR to
repatriate the remaining 4,000 Vietnamese and Cambodian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The number of Vietnamese refugees in Galang reached more than
40,000 in 1989, but many have since been resettled in third
countries, including Australia, Canada, Japan, the United States
and some west European countries. Others have returned to Hanoi,
the reports added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
