<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar weakened
against the US dollar today to close at 78.99 US cents from
Wednesday's finish of 79.20 US cents.
</P>
<P>
Comments made by the World Bank about the dual currency Samurai
bonds caused investors to sell the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Samurai bonds are issued in Japanese yen and are redeemable in
Australian dollars. Expected issuance of Samurai bonds boosted
demand for the Australian dollar and helped to prop the currency
up against other currencies in the past week.
</P>
<P>
However, the World Bank said today that issuers of Samurai
bonds were too "enthusiastic," causing "knee-jerk" selling of the
Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Australian dollar ended at 86.37 Japanese
yen from 86.66 yen Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was also weaker against the German mark, ending at 1.2055
mark from 1.2114 mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
