<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Urges G-7 to Reduce Africa's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Prime Mimister Meles Zenawi
today urged the G-7 countries to take concrete, all-inclusive and
practical action to mitigate Africa's crushing debt burden.
</P>
<P>
In a message he sent to President Jacque Chirac, chairman of
the summit of the G-7 countries which opens today in Leon,
France, Meles expressed his hope that the summit will give top
priority in its discussion to Africa's debt and development aid
to the continent.
</P>
<P>
As the current chairman of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU), Meles thanked the G-7 countries for the measures so far
they took to reduce Africa's debt.
</P>
<P>
But development aid to the continent is declining while
conditions set out by donors are self-contradictory and have
impacted the quality and execution of aid, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meles said African countries have shown determination to take
full responsibility to reverse economic decline characterized by
conflicts in countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
Unless supported by the G-7 industrialized countries in the
world, namely the United States, Canada, France, Italy, Germany,
United Kingdom and Japan, African nations can hardly bring about
sustainable development for the benefit of their peoples, Meles
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
