<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Benxi's Sustainable Development Mode Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has praised
Benxi, an industrial city in northeast China's Liaoning Province,
for its outstanding achievements in environmental protection and
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Located in the mountainous area of Liaoning, Benxi is a leading
raw materials production base in the country. It became one of
China's most polluted cities in the late 1970s, and it was said
that even satellites could not detect it.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the city has adopted measures to clean up the
air by introducing different production methods and launching new
industries that use recyclable materials.
</P>
<P>
The city also promoted eco-agriculture and planted trees to
protect its environment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the Chinese government had spent a
total of 570 million yuan (about 69 million US dollars) to solve
the city's environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas You, a UN official, told Benxi Mayor Li Yingjie that
some countries say China ignores sustainable development, which is
not true in light of the efforts made by Benxi to protect the
environment.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the city worked out a sustainable development plan,
which was listed as one of the most important projects of the
national development plan for the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
