<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Economy to Grow Faster in 1997: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economy is expected
to rise faster in 1997, according to Natwest Markets, the
investment banking arm of the British Natwest Group.
</P>
<P>
Charles Li, the firm's head of economic research for Northeast
Asia, Hong Kong's economic growth will rebound to 5.1 percent in
1997 although it is slowing down this year,
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's gross domestic product grew by 4.6 percent last
year. The government forecast 5.0 percent growth for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Hong Kong's greater economic links with the
Chinese mainland would promote rather than hinder its economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's greater links with the Chinese mainland means that
Hong Kong's economy has become more dependent on the performance
of China's emerging economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's economy will grow at an average of 10 percent over the
next five years and it is expected to become a global economic
superpower in the next century, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the year 1997 is not the end of Hong Kong's
prosperity. Hong Kong will continue to develop after the 1997
handover.  
</P>
</TEXT>
