<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent Action Urged to Tackle Environment Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A report prepared by 200
Australian scientists and specialists, circulated here today,
calls for urgent action to address pressing environmental problems
in the country's cities, regions and rural lands.
</P>
<P>
The State of the Environment report also highlights the poor
progress in addressing greenhouse gas emissions, saying energy
related carbon dioxide emissions has grown much faster than the
average for members of the Organization for Economic Development
and Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Set in motion two years ago by the former federal government,
these scientists and specialists examined a range of natural and
cultural issues affecting the protection of the country's
environment.
</P>
<P>
The habitats of Australia's rich diversity of species are being
destroyed at an alarming rate, the report says. Australian is
thought to be home to one million species, but only 15 percent of
these have been recorded.
</P>
<P>
The loss of biological diversity was perhaps the country's most
serious environmental problem, the report notes, adding that land
clearing was a major factor, with more than 600,000 hectares of
native vegetation cleared each year.
</P>
<P>
About 14 billion tons of soil was removed from Australia each
year, while some 29 million hectares of mainly agricultural land
were significantly acidified, it adds.
</P>
<P>
Other serious environmental problems listed in the report are:
</P>
<P>
-- Weeds cost the country 3.3 billion Australian dollars (2.5
billion US dollars) a year; and insects caused primary production
losses of around 3.1 billion Australian dollars (2.38 billion US
dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
-- Motor vehicle emissions were the major contributors to air
pollution in the cities, motor vehicle emissions were likely to be
a major concern in areas of rapid urban expansion, average energy
consumption rose 37 percent per person between 1970 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
-- Prevalence of asthma could be as high as 30 percent and
appeared to have doubled in the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
