<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Starts Cross-Border Operations against PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Armed Forces started to
stage cross-border military operations in northern Iraq in a bid
to wipe out the rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK), the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that a commando union of 12 battalions of the
security forces, 250 village guards and many special action teams
had staged military operations in northern Iraq with the support
of cobra helicopters starting from Semdinli town of Hakkari
province bordering Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Turkish security forces have stayed in the
areas of Butine, Ispindari, Sipa, Edilbi and Meros in northern
Iraq, adding that the Turkish government troops had exchanged
fires with the PKK rebels between the areas of Ispindari and Meros.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces have entered into 25 kilometers
deep into northern Iraq and will go as far as Meri region in
northern Iraq, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 12-year guerrilla war in
southeastern Turkey for self-rule and has been attacking military
and civilian targets in Turkey from northern Iraq. More than
20,000 people including PKK rebels, civilians and government
troops have been killed since the PKK started fighting in August
1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
