<HEADLINE> Egypt to build More Warehouses to Store Antiquities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will build a number of modern
warehouses to store antiquities as there are not enough museums to
house all the unearthed artifacts.
</P>
<P>
According to Egypt's only English-language daily The Egyptian
Gazette today, many existing warehouses in the country are
suffering from bad storage methods and poor ventilation.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces Agency for National Service Projects has been
assigned to build five new warehouses, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Abdul Halim Nureddin, Secretary General of the
Higher Council of Antiquities, as saying that a total of at least
15 new warehouses will be built, with each one covering an area of
2,500 square meters and costing an estimated 1 million Egyptian
pounds (294,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said that the warehouses will be equipped with the most
up-to-date anti-fire and anti-theft systems and display cases with
humidity and temperature controls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
