<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Repatriates 99 Vietnamese Boat People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The remaining 99 Vietnamese boat
people who had been in Singapore since 1990, were repatriated this
afternoon, as a Vietnam Airline flight took them back to the Ho
Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
Danilo Bautista, head of the Liaison Office of the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), said at a press
conference at the Changi Airport shortly before the repatriation
that the 99 boat people left Singapore today under the UNHCR's
Voluntary Repatriation Program.
</P>
<P>
The 99 repatriants consisted of 60 male and 20 female adults,
13 male and six female children. This group was the last group of
Vietnamese boat people remaining in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
They had been living in the Hawkins Road Camp, which is located
in the northern part of Singapore, and administered by the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
Since 1975, Singapore has hosted a total of 32,457 Vietnamese
boat people, Bautista said, adding that the great majority of
32,364 were resettled to third countries.
</P>
<P>
Loo Cheng Yan, Singapore's Controller of Immigration, said at
the press conference that the Vietnamese Boat People (VBP) had
been allowed to enter Singapore in the first instance because of
the unconditional written guarantees of seven western countries to
resettle the Vietnamese boat people within three months of their
arrival in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"However, these guarantor countries have failed to honor their
commitments. As a result, the Vietnamese boat people have been
left stranded in Singapore, many since the early 1990s," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Singapore government has always treated the
Vietnamese boat people in a humane manner. "Unlike the camps in
the other countries, the Hawkins Road Camp was not a closed camp
and the Vietnamese boat people were not kept under surveillance,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that many Vietnamese boat people even found
employment outside the camp and managed to accumulate an average
of 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 2,143 US dollars) each as
savings.
</P>
<P>
As all 99 of them agreed to return to Vietnam under the
Voluntary Repatriation Program, he said, the Singapore government
has given Human Financial Assistance of 760 US dollars to each of
the Vietnamese boat people "as a further gesture of goodwill".
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of the last group of Vietnamese boat people in
Singapore started on June 13, this year, as the UNHCR had decided
to close all its camps in the region by June 30.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uneven Road to Reconciliation Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan has embarked on a
rough road towards reconciliation as Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, chief of
the Afghan Hezb-i-Islami, took oath as prime minister of a new
coalition government, with his old rival Burhanuddin Rabbani
remaining as the president.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar entered the capital city of Kabul Wednesday after
heavy shelling and rocket attacks by the Taliban militia who had
tried to stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time in the past 16 years that Hekmatyar
made himself available in the city, and the second time for him to
assume the premiership under Rabbani's presidency.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar, 50, is a major representative of Pushtuns who
account for nearly half of the Afghan population, while Rabbani is
a Tajik.
</P>
<P>
As far back as in the former Soviet occupation from 1979 to
1989, the Afghan resistance groups were marked with ethnic feud
and power struggle, which led to a number of clashes between
Hekmatyar's Hezb-i-Islami guerrilla and Rabbani's Jamiat-i-Islami
forces.
</P>
<P>
After the Soviet withdrawal in 1989 and the collapse of the
Najibullah regime in 1992, both Hekmatyar and Rabbani rushed to
Kabul to grab the central power of the country, igniting the
factional fighting that is still going on today.
</P>
<P>
Under a power-sharing pact -- the Islamabad Accord -- signed by
various Afghan parties in April 1993, Hekmatyar was appointed the
prime minister of the then government and Rabbani the president.
</P>
<P>
However, Hekmatyar refused to go into Kabul to exercise his
power, saying that he feared assassination plots by Rabbani's men
who had already occupied most parts of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The strife between the two men reached an apex on January 1,
1994, when Hekmatyar attempted a coup with Rashid Dostum, leader
of Uzbek militia, against the Rabbani regime.
</P>
<P>
With the coup attempt failing, Hekmatyar and Dostum established
a four-party opposition alliance, which included Hezb-i-Wahdat
headed by Abdul Mazari, who was killed by the Taliban in 1995, and
Nejat-i-Melli led by Mojaddedi.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban militia, a new player in the Afghan bloody
drama, emerged surprisingly at the end of 1994 and gave several
heavy blows to Hekmatyar's troops during its campaign aimed at
wiping out all the warlords in the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, both Hekmatyar and Rabbani tried to draw the Taliban
over to his side, but the Taliban decided to erase both of them.
</P>
<P>
The student militia has been seeking to besiege Kabul since
October 1995, after capturing most of the Hekmatyar-held territory
and some under Rabbani's control.
</P>
<P>
Facing the growing common threat, delegates of Hekmatyar and
Rabbani started secret contacts at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Despite threats from the Taliban and objection from his
partners in the opposition alliance, Hekmatyar signed a
reconciliation pact with Rabbani near Kabul on May 24 this year.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani made some concessions by offering Hekmatyar's side
portfolios of prime minister, defense and financial ministers in a
new coalition government. Rabbani's side still retains the key
positions of president, interior, foreign and national security
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani later also allowed Hekmatyar's troops to enter Kabul in
a bid to jointly defend the capital.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that it is a major step in the Afghan
peace process that the two old rivals have rejoined hands. It
might become a model for other rival groups to improve their
relations.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still too early to say that the long-running
Afghan conflict will switch to a road of peace.
</P>
<P>
The observers said the peace process would be difficult without
the participation of the Taliban, which has a large military force
and controls half of the Afghan territory.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, vowing to topple Rabbani's regime and unite the
whole country by itself, has termed the new government as
illegitimate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Control Pork Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has decided
to take emergency measures to curb the rapidly increasing imports
of pork, effective for nine months from next Monday, Kyodo News
Service reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Following the import curbs, the price of pork for making
processed ham and sausage will go up by about 24 percent from the
present 450.02 yen per kilogram to 557.19 yen, officials of the
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The new price will raise manufacturing costs at meat processors.
</P>
<P>
However, processors are now finding it hard to raise prices of
ham and sausage because of slow consumer spending, said an
official.
</P>
<P>
In just April and May, Japan's pork imports exceeded the
standard average by 19 percent, according to data released
Thursday by the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Imports account for about a third of Japan's total pork
supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
