<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TAZARA Changes for Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania-Zambia Railway
authority (TAZARA) is changing for the better with new facilities
installed to make it an important rail link of the southern
Africa region network.
</P>
<P>
TAZARA has installed new computerized communication facilities
such as the rail tracker, an advanced technical system capable of
doing 70 percent of work, the local press today quoted Joseph
Minsula, TAZARA Director of Marketing and Traffic, as saying.
</P>
<P>
With the new rail tracker system, TAZARA is able to track any
locomotive with ease and a customer can be advised of the
position of his cargo within seconds by use of the advanced cargo
information system computer, Minsula said.
</P>
<P>
Now TAZARA has a huge marshalling yard at Yombo Station a short
distance from Dar es Salaam to ensure speedy assembling and dispatch
of wagons, according to the TAZARA director.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the problems "in communicating information to
customers on transportation of their goods," TAZARA has "decided
to put up these computerized systems in order to compete with
other traffickers", the director said.
</P>
<P>
The revamping of the communication system has built confidence
in customers who in the past complained of having been kept "in
communicado", the director added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, TAZARA has made improvements in clearing
and forwarding frieght services, security system and express
passenger trains.
</P>
<P>
The 1,860-kilometer TAZARA from the New Capiri Mposhi of Zambia to
Dar es Salaam in Tazania is now equipped with adequate facilities
to deal with 5 million tons of freight a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
