<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Oil Output to Reach 200 Million Tons in 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China's onshore oil output is
rising steadily and will reach 200 million tons in the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tao, president of the China National Petroleum
Corporation, said that will represent an increase of one third
over the present annual output of about 150 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"China will still rank fifth in the world in oil production at
that time," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The senior official explained that the country's onshore oil
strategy of stabilizing the output in eastern China's aging
oilfields, and developing new oilfields in western China has
started to pay off.
</P>
<P>
By injecting water into the ground to maintain oil output, old
oilfields in eastern China, which produce over 80 percent of the
country's total output, have succeeded in controlling the rate of
natural output decline within 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the oilfields have accelerated prospecting to push
oil production capacity to 64 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Wang expects that by the year 2000 the old oilfields in eastern
China will maintain their output at the current 120 million
tons. While Daqing, China's leading oilfield, will maintain its
annual crude output of 50 million tons until the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
According to the senior official, western China has seen
fruitful results in oil exploration and production. Some 9 large
oil and gas fields, each with oil reserves between 50 million tons
and 100 million tons, have been discovered in the Tarim, Junggar
and Turpan-Hami basins in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
To date Xinjiang has verified total geological oil reserves of
1.94 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that the coming 15 years will be the
heyday for Xinjiang's oil production. The annual oil output there
is expected to hit 25.9 million tons by the year 2000, or 16
millions tons more than the 1995 figure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
