<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossilized dinosaur Eggs Found in Liaoning Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A nest of ten fossilized dinosaur
eggs, about 100 million years old, have been found in Yueliang
Village, Xiaerjiazi Township, Changtu County, northeast China's
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The eggs were discovered when workers from a construction
company in Anshan City were driving a pile 16 meters below the
surface for the construction of a bridge on an expressway from
Tieling to Siping.
</P>
<P>
Some of the eggs were broken and all of the eggs have
shells. But five or six eggs were later stolen.
</P>
<P>
Ning Tian, head of a construction team, sent the rest to the
Liaoning Provincial Institute of Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists expressed the belief that the eggs were dated
from some 100 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
The eggs were smaller than most dinosaur eggs, about the size
of a goose egg. Most of them are oval and one has a flat shape.
</P>
<P>
Dong Zhiming, a dinosaur researcher with the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, said, "such small dinosaur eggs are really very rare. I
think probably they were laid by some new species of
dinosaurs. But I don't know what species."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
