<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Aquatic Animals Given Special Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen, known as a "garden upon the
sea," has set up nature reserves to protect rare aquatic animals
such as the white-flag dolphin, the lancelet and the green turtle.
</P>
<P>
The white-flag dolphin is one of the world's most endangered
species. With growing pollution in the region, the number of the
Chinese river dolphins has decreased, and now there are only about
200 -- fewer than the also-rare Giant Pandas.
</P>
<P>
After a careful investigation, experts mastered the
distribution information of the white-flag dolphin, then
established a preservation zone to give special protection to the
rare aquatic mammal.
</P>
<P>
The Fujian Provincial Government also made great efforts to
preserve the lancelet, which mainly live in the coastal areas of
Xiamen in east China's Fujian Province. Lancelet is important for
the study of the evolution from the invertebrate to the
vertebrate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Province Beats Grain Shortages to End Rationing for Millions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The issue of grain had long stemmed the economic development of
Liaoning, which paid attention only to the industrial expansion
until 1978, when the central and local governments began to grant
more funds, popularize agro-technology in rural areas, and
mobilize farmers' enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
As a result Liaoning's annual grain output jumped to 12 billion
kilograms in the 1980s, and 15 billion kilograms in 1990, meeting
by and large the needs of the province's 43 million people, one
half of whom are urban citizens.
</P>
<P>
Last year saw Liaoning experience severe flood, but it still
reaped a grain output of 14.235 billion kilograms, averaging 350
kilograms per capita.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Wencai, deputy governor of the province,
Liaoning's self-sufficiency in grain supply has not only help the
province to develop industrialization and urbanization, but also
alleviated the burdens of other provinces, which had to supply
Liaoning with an average of 2.5 billion kilograms of grain a year
from the 1950s to the end of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
After inspecting Liaoning province, Yang Yongzhe, deputy
director of the Development Research Center under the State
Council, spoke highly of the province for "setting an example for
coastal provinces and regions in solving the grain problem."
</P>
<P>
"It has enhanced the Chinese government's confidence in the
country's self-sufficiency in grain and non-staple food supply,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a stable grain production, Liaoning has vowed to
boost its annual grain output up to 17.5 billion kilograms by the
end of this century through increasing input, further protecting
farmland, spreading advanced agro-techniques while controlling the
population, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
