<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jilin Turns Sandy Land into Granary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The western part of northeast
China's Jilin Province, which used to be large tracts of barren
sandy land, has become a new granary in the province due to
improvements in the ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
The province is constructing shelter belts for farmland to
control damage from sandstorms, forestry experts said.
</P>
<P>
More than 170,000 ha of shelter forests have been planted in
the grain producing area in the west, which protect 2.53 million
ha of farmland with an annual output increase of 2.15 billion kg,
the experts said.
</P>
<P>
The province started the afforestation project to control
shifting sand in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The area now subject to sandstorm damage has decreased from 7.3
million ha in the 1970s to 310,000 ha, and the area of sandy land
decreased by 1.1 million ha, they said, adding that the western
region has the greatest potential for agricultural production in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Jilin will increase its grain output by five billion kg during
the Ninth Five-year Plan (1996-2000) period, and 1.9 billion kg of
the planned grain output increase is expected to come from the
west. It now produces 1.9 billion kg of grain annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
