<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Nonhemophiliacs Die After Receiving Tainted Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Seven people have already died from
AIDS after receiving blood products possibly tainted with AIDS
virus, Kyodo News Service quoted the Health and Welfare Ministry
as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They were among at least 12 nonhemophiliacs who were infected
with HIV after receiving blood products possibly tainted with the
virus, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry learned this as a result of its nationwide survey
with medical institutions to investigate how many nonhemophiliac
patients received unheated blood products in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows a total of 292 medical institutions in the
nation used the dangerous products during treatment for 2,233
nonhemophiliac patients, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Of the patients, 1,419 or about two-thirds were liver disease
patients and new-born babies. The seven who have died of AIDS
include an unknown number of such babies.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has confirmed that 1,511 of the total patients had
already died before the survey began, making it impossible to tell
whether they were HIV positive or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Scientists Develop a Magnetic Thin Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A group of Japanese scientists have
developed a new type of magnetic thin film that could enable
computers to record considerably more data than they currently do,
Kyodo News Service reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They subjected carbon and cobalt plates to ion beams and
collected the particles which flew off on a glass substrate at
temperatures between 200 and 300 C.
</P>
<P>
The resulting particles in the film deposited on the glass
averaged 7 nanometers in diameter.
</P>
<P>
Magnetic film currently used to record data in computers uses a
cobalt-derived alloy, but the newly developed membrane has cobalt
crystals which are between half and a third the size of
conventional ones, they said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, since the cobalt nanocrystals in the newly
developed membrane are isolated from each other by the
graphite-like carbon, it has considerable potential as a medium
for recording data.
</P>
<P>
The scientists work at the NTT Interdisciplinary Research
Laboratories in Musashino, western Tokyo. The group includes
Takayoshi Hayashi, Shigeru Hirono, Masato Tomita and Shigeru
Umemura. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
