<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Province Beats Grain Shortages to End Rationing for Millions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
province has sown the seeds of success -- and said goodbye to the
days of grain rationing for its massive population of town and
city dwellers.
</P>
<P>
The province's drive for grain self sufficiency was put to the
ultimate test in the past year when severe floods swept the area.
</P>
<P>
But Liaoning, China's leading heavy industrial base, reaped a
good harvest of 14-billion kilograms of grain -- enough to feed
its 43 million people of the province. There was also plenty of
grains to spare.
</P>
<P>
Now provincial leaders say the success is helping to boost the
province's mainstay industries by attracting investors.
</P>
<P>
They say that gone are the days when Liaoning was force to
purchased grain from outside to feed its own people.
</P>
<P>
A new survey shows that farmers in the Northeast China province
still have between 700 million and 800 million kilograms of
surplus grain in hand during the current temporary grain shortage
period -- the time when the new crop is still in the blade and the
old one has all been consumed.
</P>
<P>
In addition the province has put at least 220 million kilograms
of stored grain on the market each month to ensure the grain
supply.
</P>
<P>
An 80-square-meter grain shop in Huanggu district in Shenyang,
the provincial capital, was serving one afternoon only one
customer, an elderly woman who was buying ten kilograms of rice.
</P>
<P>
"Just a few years ago we were so busy selling grain to queues
of people waiting for their grain rations that we did not have
time to have lunch during similar grain-off seasons," said a shop
assistant, who disclosed that the grain ration system was
cancelled because of the sufficient supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
