<HEADLINE> China's First SOS Children's Village Celebrates 10th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China's first SOS village in the
port city of Tianjin has held celebrations to mark the 10th
anniversary of its founding.
</P>
<P>
China now has five other SOS villages -- in Yantai in Shandong
Province, Qiqihar in Heilongjiang Province, Nanchang in Jiangxi
Province and Chengdu in Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The 6,600-sq m village was sponsored by the municipal
government of Tianjin and the international SOS village
organization.
</P>
<P>
There are 18 families in the SOS village in Tianjin. "Mothers,"
who are mostly single women, devote their lives and love to the
orphans. They have become "mothers" of 208 orphans, and brought up
40 of them.
</P>
<P>
The "mothers" not only look after the daily needs of the
youngsters, but also learn psychology, and develop the childrens'
special skills.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 300 SOS children's villages in some 100
countries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The world's first children's village was launched by Austrian
doctor Hermann Gmeiner in 1949. The SOS movement is a charity
organization. The villages are made up of families, each with a
"mother" and between five and eight children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
