<HEADLINE> More Middle School Students Aspiring to CPC Membership (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics provided by the Central Committee of the Communist
Youth League of China show that there are 15,159 student-CPC
members in senior and junior middle schools across the country,
with the majority in the senior years.
</P>
<P>
As an important reserve force of society, middle school
students, particularly the estimated 16.52 million seniors, are
expected to become backbones in various trades in the early
decades of the 21st century, and play a pivotal role in achieving
China's modernization targets. Therefore their beliefs and choices
are attracting increasing close attention.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Sheng, a 19-year-old student leader with the Shude Middle
School in Chengdu, has filed four application letters to Party
branches requesting for admission, but still remains on the list
of applicants "under consideration".
</P>
<P>
"I shall not give up my pursuit," he said, steadfastly and
undeterred.
</P>
<P>
Zhong's grandfather was mistaken as a so-called "Rightist" in
the 1950s and expelled from the Party. Firm in his belief in
Communism, he applied for admission to the CPC for 20 years
running and was finally readmitted in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
"Through Grandpa I felt the enormous inspiration and influence
of the Communist Party on an ordinary Chinese citizen," Zhong
Sheng said, "I will follow the suit of Grandpa and hold firm my
belief in joining the Party."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
