<HEADLINE> More Middle School Students Aspiring to CPC Membership (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Facing the symbolic "axe and
sickle" red flag hanging on a wall, Gaisang Dagwa, middle school
student in Chengdu, capital city of southwest China's Sichuan
province, raised his right hand and took a solemn oath to dedicate
himself to the cause of Communism.
</P>
<P>
"I am lucky and proud of being admitted to the Chinese
Communist Party," Gaisang Dagwa, of the Tibet Middle School in
Chengdu, told Xinhua after the swearing ceremony held on the eve
of the 75th anniversary of the founding of the CPC.
</P>
<P>
Gaisang, 18, is chairman of the Students Federation in his
school, where the Party branch graded him as "excellent in both
learning and moral character."
</P>
<P>
At the same time 16 other students were sworn in to the Party
ranks, bringing the city's current middle school student-Party
membership to 50, according to the Party Organization Department
of Chengdu City Education Commission. The department said that
currently more students were actively applying for, and striving
to qualify for Party membership.
</P>
<P>
Over 98 percent of the 40,000 middle school students in Chengdu
said they believe in Communism, and 95 percent of them expressed
the hope of becoming CPC members, with 70 percent having already
filed applications to joining the Party, according to a latest
survey.
</P>
<P>
Chen Deshu, a sociologist with the Sichuan Provincial Academy
of Social Sciences, attributed the upsurge of middle school
students applying for Party membership to popularity of Communist
ideals among young Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamental cause behind the phenomenon lies in the
remarkable success of reforms the CPC has launched, " he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Party Constitution, Chinese citizens above the age of
18 are eligible to apply for Party membership.
</P>
</TEXT>
