<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 07:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Launches Water Saving Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government has
launched a water saving campaign to combat the anticipated summer
drought.
</P>
<P>
"Forget the Turks, water is our biggest problem," Lakis
Christodoulou, Director of the Cyprus' Water Development Division,
was quoted as saying today.
</P>
<P>
He noted that reservoirs are only 37 percent full, compared
to 59.6 percent at the same period last year. People need to be
reminded to conserve water wherever possible.
</P>
<P>
According to the director, the water department is also
implementing a number of water-saving measures.
</P>
<P>
Supply to water boards is to be cut by 10 percent, while
water for agricultural use will be cut by between 25 and 40
percent. There will also be a strict ban on hosepipes for washing
pavements or cars and 100 Cyprus pounds (about 200 U.S. dollars)
grants available for town dwellers to sink boreholes in their
gardens for irrigation water.
</P>
<P>
In the long-term, the Water Development Division is planning
to build more dams.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever water we have this year was saved last year --
without dams we would have no water now," Christodoulou said.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island, mainly relies on rainfall
for water supply, already has more reservoirs per square
kilometer than any other European countries, with 101 dams now
operational -- most of them built since the country's
independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
"We also want to use more water from sewage treatment plants,
mostly for soccer pitches and golf courses, where quality is not
so crucial," the director said.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the water supply shortage, the island's first
desalination plant is due to start operating in 1997. It will
supply 20,000 cubic meters of water a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
