<HEADLINE> Jordan, Israel Investigating Border Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Israel are investigating
an terrorist attack on Israeli border patrol along the
Jordanian-Israeli borders Wednesday morning, which killed three
Israeli soldier and wounded two others.
</P>
<P>
The attack, the worst armed incident along the border since
the two countries signed a peace treaty in October, 1994,
occurred at about 8 a.m. Wednesday when an Israeli border patrol
was ambushed by unidentified gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Reports said a routine Israeli patrol vehicle was fired upon
from "very close range by terrorists who apparently came from
Jordan."
</P>
<P>
Following the attack, King Hussein of Jordan expressed his
condolences to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for the
victims.
</P>
<P>
However, an official Jordanian statement released Wednesday
said that there was no indications to suggest the armed group had
infiltrated from Jordanian territories or had retreated to them.
</P>
<P>
A senior Jordanian government official was quoted by the
English-language daily Jordan Times today as saying that details
had yet to be confirmed and this would be achieved through a
joint Jordan-Israel investigation already in progress.
</P>
<P>
"We have yet to confirm the details of the incident and
the parties behind it and we are conducting a joint
investigation with the Israelis in line with the Jordan-Israel
peace treaty," the official added.
</P>
<P>
But, no certain information about whether the infiltrators did
in fact originate from Jordan was available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
