<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Speeds Up Bankruptcy in Old Industrial Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese machinery plant
employing 8,000 people has become the biggest state-owned
enterprise in the country to be forced into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Managers of the 60-year-old plant in northeast China's Lioning
province applied to the court for liquidation.
</P>
<P>
The Third Machine Tool Plant of Shenyang has suffered losses
for years due to poor management performance.
</P>
<P>
As a large manufacturer, it boasts 400 million yuan worth of
assets. But its total debts are far higher, hitting 650 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The plant has been called a "vegetable firm" by Shenyang's
deputy mayor Jiang Xianzhi.
</P>
<P>
"They keep losing money and all efforts have been tried to no
avail, so they have to quit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang is the capital of Liaoning Province, which is one of
China's old heavy industrial bases and has 1,400 large and
medium-sized state-owned enterprises, one-tenth of the nation's
total.
</P>
<P>
In 1986, the then Shenyang Explosive-proof Equipment Factory, a
small firm with less than 60 workers, became the first in China to
be declared bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
As the market mechanism has been playing a more important role,
some large and medium-sized enterprises in Liaoning have taken a
turn for the better, and some have become worse off, provincial
governor Wen Shizhen said.
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy cases of large and medium-sized state-owned
enterprises have continued to rise for the past two years, mainly
because of outdated technology and equipment, poor product
mix and inefficient management, Wen said.
</P>
<P>
While 30 percent of large and medium-sized firms are in good
shape at present, some 20 percent are said to be on the verge of
closing down, according to a survey by the provincial Economic and
Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
"If those hopeless 20 percent continue to exist, they will
simply waste more resources," said Wu Qicheng, the commission's
deputy director.
</P>
<P>
The central authorities have asked and supported the provincial
government to speed up renovation of the old industrial base, with
bankruptcy recognized as one of the effective ways.
</P>
<P>
The province witnessed its first bankruptcy case of a large and
medium-sized state-owned enterprise in 1994, followed by 16
similar cases in 1995. In an accelerated process, the figure for
this year soared to 62 by June 10.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that all bankrupt firms have been purchased by other
enterprises, which have made adequate use of their assets for
other production purposes.
</P>
<P>
During bankruptcy processes, local governments have given
priority to new assignment of workers in those firms. Nearly
30,000 such workers have either found other jobs or received
social benefits, and no social unrest has occurred, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Provincial governor Wen holds that in a market economy, it's
natural that some enterprises will survive and others will die.
</P>
<P>
"We don't need to maintain all the state-owned firms in our
province. We just strive to enliven a majority, or two-thirds, of
them, and that will be good enough," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
