<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0730 GMT, June 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian government today denied "any form of
Iran's involvement" in the Dhahran explosion which killed Tuesday
night at least 19 U.S. soldiers and injured 386 others in Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Mohammadi, a spokesman of the Iranian Foreign Ministry,
accused both the United States and Israel of brewing joint plots
to mar the prestige of Iran. "Attribution of such acts to Iran
arises from the U.S. and Israel's long standing hostility to Islam
and Iran," he was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also rejected the baseless accusations leveled
against the sovereignty of Iran by the Israeli regime, calling
Israeli President Ezer Weizman and U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher as the elements supporting and masterminding state
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The United States would not reduce its armed
forces stationed in the Gulf region, U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said Christopher, who arrived in
Saudi Arabia Wednesday, made the remarks to reporters while paying
a visit to the scene of the truck explosion which killed at least
19 U.S. soldiers and wounded 386 others.
</P>
<P>
Christopher said his country would not yield to terrorist
threats and would be "very decisive while dealing with such
threats."
</P>
<P>
Christopher was accompanied during his visit to the blast site
by Saudi Foreign Minister Saoud Al-Faisal.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic will not run
in the country's elections on September 14 and has agreed to
resign as "president" after the poll, but only on certain
conditions, a senior Bosnian Serb official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"In agreement with the Bosnian Serb leadership and due to the
horrible pressures by the international community and the
Yugoslavia, Karadzic decided not to take part in the elections,"
Bosnian Serb Prime Minister Gojko Klickovic told reporters in
Banja Luka in northwestern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic's decision is conditional on a guarantee by the
international community to recognize the self-declared Republika
Srpska, the Serb entity in Bosnia, as a state with full
sovereignty within Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He is also demanding that the international arbitrators
deciding the fate of the northern town of Brcko guarantee to give
the town to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Brcko, a port town linking the Bosnian Serbs' eastern and
western territories, is currently held by the Serbs who see it as
vital for their strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- U.S. President Bill Clinton arrived in the
southeastern French city of Lyon Wedensday for a summit of the
Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized nations, which is to open
today.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reportedly said before leaving the White House that the
fight against terrorism has become the "first order of our
business."
</P>
<P>
"Our first order of business will be to focus the strength and
the energy of the G-7 on the continuing fight against terrorism,"
said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Defeating these organized forces of destruction is one of the
most important challenges our country faces at the end of this
century and at the beginning of the next," the president added.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism, which has already been on the agenda of the
three-day summit, is expected to be given more attention as other
leaders of the seven countries echoed Clinton's remarks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
