<HEADLINE> Huge Salamander Returned to Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-six baby giant
salamanders, artificially hatched by a doctor in central China's
Hunan province, were released into the Wushui River Monday night,
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth time Wang Cunlu, a doctor who works in the
Hospital of the Zhijiang Ethnic Dong Group Autonomous County, has
returned the giant salamander to nature over the past four
years. The rare animal is under the state's Class 2 protection.
</P>
<P>
In April, 1992, Wang found four fish eggs in a mountain brook
near the county and took them home.
</P>
<P>
At the time, he was applying for a patent for an invention that
provided food and a safe environment for goldfish.
</P>
<P>
Wang put the four eggs into his invention, which feeds the eggs
with a liquid source of nutrition, and successfully incubated
them. The four fish grew fast in his invention, and weighed one
kg a year later.
</P>
<P>
Wang continues his work in artificial fish incubation, and his
method is deemed as a breakthrough in the field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
