<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 07:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Official Confirmed to Have Met Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Officials from Israeli prime
minister's office confirmed today that a senior government
official has met with top Palestinian Negotiator Mahmoud Abbas,
which marked the first time a Likud government official met with
the PLO.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was secretly held last Wednesday between Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's foreign policy adviser Dore Gold
and Abbas, also known as Abu Mazen, in the West Bank town of
Ramallah or Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The officials declined to give any further details about the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media pointed out that the meeting was timed to
coincide with the eve of the Cairo Arab summit, held last
weekend, and designed to ease Palestinian concerns before parley.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gold refused to comment on the meeting, saying he
would not discuss anything related to Palestinian contacts.
</P>
<P>
It remained unclear what the two discussed, but it appears
that Gold conveyed the government's desire for a sincere dialogue
with the Palestinians and its willingness to set up negotiating
teams for the future.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after his election victory on May 29, Netanyahu
authorized Gold to make initial phone contact with Abbas, making
it the first time the Likud has officially made contact with the
PLO.
</P>
<P>
Gold then said he was "authorized to convey to Abbas that a
mechanism of contact with the Palestinian (National) Authority
will be made once the government is formed."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Netanyahu said last night that
there would be a variety of channels in dealing with the
Palestinians, and this could involve the ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
However, he refused to say if or under what conditions he
would meet with Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Officials believed that a meeting between Arafat
and Netanyahu was essential before any serious talks can begin on
the future of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking for high-level talks, and that means Arafat
and Netanyahu," said Arafat's aide Nabil Abu Rudeineh.
</P>
<P>
When it happens, "I am sure the first meeting between Arafat
and Netanyahu will be difficult, but I am sure it will be less
difficult than the first meeting between Arafat and Yitzhak
Rabin," the assassinated Israeli premier, said Ahmed Tibi, a close
adviser to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security sources also expected that such a meeting
will be necessary before any Israeli army's redeployment in
the disputed West Bank town of Hebron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
