<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Not to Succumb to Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government will not
succumb to pressure from international financiers in terms of
privatization until the indigenous people have the capacity to
take over, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe has said.
</P>
<P>
Local reports quoted Mugabe as saying in Ghanaian capital
Accra on Wednesday it would be senseless to privatize now
although commercialization of various departments and parastatals
was underway.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we have said to the IMF (International Monetary
Fund), we do not need to be rushed into privatizing," he said
when launching the African Capital Markets Forum at the
International Conference on Reviving Private Investment in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Too many multinationals have already controlled key sectors of
Zimbabwe's economy, such as mining, according to the president.
</P>
<P>
If privatization preceded indigenisation, the parastatals and
government departments would fall into the hands of "just a group
of settlers", Mugabe warned.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the white minority, which represents
about one percent of Zimbabwe's population of about 10.5 million,
controls about 80 percent of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF last September suspended disbursement of the
100-million-US-Dollar balance of payments aid to Zimbabwe because
the government had failed to meet some major targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
