<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electricity Tariffs Up in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Electricity Supply
Authority (ZESA) announced here yesterday that electricity
tariffs will go up by an average 18 percent from July 1, exactly
a year after the last round of tariff increases.
</P>
<P>
ZESA said in a statement, "for the 12 months since the last
review, the rate of inflation of the national economy has remained
above 20 percent."
</P>
<P>
"The Zimbabwe Dollar has not yet stabilized appreciably. In
fact the local currency has continued to weaken against the
currencies of the major trading partners," according to the ZESA.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign debt constitutes 25 percent of our costs, while
imports of electricity which are paid for in foreign currency
constitute 20 percent of total expenditure," it added.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the prices of liquid fuel and coal
were also reported up by significant increases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
