<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 07:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Calls for Actions Against Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu has called on the international community to take
"necessary actions" against Syria if it "continues on the path of
terror."
</P>
<P>
In an interview published in today's English daily Jerusalem
Post, Netanyahu avoided using the phrase of "triple containment,"
which he used before the elections involving the same sort of
sanctions imposed by the U.S. against Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"It's not a containment policy. It's simply a policy that says
that we're not going to play by Syrian rules," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
"Syrian rules are that they lash out with terrorism 360
degrees, obviously against Turkey, against Jordan, and
increasingly against us, and I don't mean only Hezbollah," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu pointed out that the extremist Islamic militant
movements, including Hamas and Islamic Jihad, are all based in
Damascus "perpetrating terrorist acts indirectly against Israeli
citizens."
</P>
<P>
"This is unacceptable. Syria has to know that a political
price will be exacted from Damascus if it continues," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu demanded the West to stop turning a blind eye to what
he called Syrian-backed terror. "I want to certainly persuade our
allies, and especially the United States, that this policy is
detrimental not only to our interests but to the interests of
others," he said.
</P>
<P>
He declined to say whether he would tell U.S. President Bill
Clinton when and under what conditions he would meet Palestinian
Authority President Yasser Arafat or pull back from Hebron during
their scheduled meeting in Washington on July 9.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who has vowed no compromise on Israel's
self-claimed sovereignty on the occupied lands, said Israel
accepts with its "own interpretation" of the U.N. Security Council
Resolution 242, regarded by others as involving trading land for
peace.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he would uphold agreements reached by previous
governments, Netanyahu said this would be contingent upon Arab
"reciprocity."
</P>
<P>
He called on the Palestinians to reconvene to revoke the
PLO Covenant, which called for the destruction of Israel, since
the Palestine National Council meeting in April constituted a
"partial step."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu suggested he favored steps to improve the
Palestinian economy, but he offered no timetable for lifting the
crippling closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip imposed since
late February following a series of suicide bomb attacks by Hamas
activists against Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
