<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 06:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Involvement in Dhahran Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
denied "any form of Iran's involvement" in the Dhahran explosion
which killed Tuesday night at least 19 U.S. soldiers and injured
386 others in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Mohammadi, a spokesman of the Iranian Foreign Ministry,
accused both the United States and Israel of brewing joint plots
to mar the prestige of Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Attribution of such acts to Iran arises from the U.S. and
Israel's long standing hostility to Islam and Iran," he was quoted
by the official news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also rejected the baseless accusations leveled
against the sovereignty of Iran by the Israeli regime, calling
Israeli President Ezer Weizman and U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher as the elements supporting and masterminding state
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He noted that dubious and wilful efforts seem to be underway
in the region in order to create suspicion among the neighboring
nations, which, in fact, is firstly aimed at paving the ground
for the expansion of Israel's political and economic influence
and finally bringing about a new regional security order, which
will be inclusive of the Israeli regime.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the regional countries are vigilant
enough to block the "ruinous U.S.-Zionist policies" which are not
only meant to create a gap between the Islamic and Arab nations in
the region but also to discredit Iran.
</P>
<P>
Weizman has implicated Iran of having a hand in the blast in
the American base in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, noting Tehran was
behind similar attacks in Lebanon and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The English daily Iran News published an editorial here today,
saying that "American forces should quit the region
unconditionally."
</P>
<P>
In principle, the daily said, "terrorism is to be
unequivocally condemned. However, regional observers believe that
such acts will continue as long as the American forces are
present in this part of the world, particularly in Saudi Arabia."
</P>
<P>
"We should not forget that Saudi Arabia, the birthplace of
Islam, enjoys a special status in the Islamic world. The country
houses Islam's holiest places, and it should be remembered that
Saudi Arabia's history is based on the Islamic principles and
that its previous rulers such as King Saud and King Faisel never
tolerated the presence of alien forces on their land," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The editorial said that the fact is that under the
circumstances prevailing in the region, Saudi Arabia does not
need the American forces at all.
</P>
<P>
"Saudi Arabia, Iran and some other regional countries are
quite capable of maintaining peace here in a friendly
atmosphere. There is no need for the American forces and they
should leave the region immediately," it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
