<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Fishermen Plan Port Blockade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Indian fishermen plan to
indefinitely lay siege to at least eight major ports in August in
protest against foreign trawlers being allowed in the Indian
waters, The Hindustan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Kocherry, chairperson of the National Fish-Workers Forum
was quoted as saying that prior to the planned blockade, he will
go on an indefinite hunger-strike pressing for the cancellation of
licenses issued to foreign fishing vessels operating on the Indian
seas.
</P>
<P>
Among the ports targeted for the blockage are Mumbai, Kandla,
Mangalore, Vasco, Vishakhapatnam, Madras, Paradip and Cochin.
</P>
<P>
The protests stem from the fear that the stock of fish will
deplete rapidly affecting the livelihood of 8 million fishermen in
the country if action is not quickly taken on the issue, reports
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
