<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Granted 11 Billion Dollars in Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania received 11.1
billion U.S. Dollars in external financing commitments between
1989 and 1995, nearbly 70 Dollars for each person every year.
</P>
<P>
Aided population for the period was hovering around 26.6
million on the average, indicating an annual per capita 69.71
Dollars for the local recipients, the United Nations Development
Programme (UNDP) announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The mainland received some 10.7 billion Dollars during the
period, while Zanzibar obtained 434.5 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Main benefactors were reported to be Denmark, the European
Union and the UNDP.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UNDP admitted in its report that funds flowing
from development agencies had been declining.
</P>
<P>
Norway's aid to Tanzania went down from 86,394,000 Dollars in
1991 to 60.1 million Dollars in 1994. The figure dropped further
down to 52 million Dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Swedish aid to Tanzania downed steadily from 124.1 million
Dollars in 1991 to 56.8 million Dollars in 1994, and then to 36.7
million Dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also reduced credit facilities from 29.2 million
Dollars in 1991 to 469,000 Dollars in 1993, although the figure
rebounded to 888,000 Dollars in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commission for Refugges (UNHCR) has on
the other hand sharply increased its assistance to Tanzania, from
706,000 Dollars in 1991 to 1.4 million in 1994, and to 46.9
million in 1995, due to an increased refugee influx from Rwanda
and Burundi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
