<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elephants One Big, Big Happy Family in Shanghai Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- One big, big happy family --
that's Shanghai's popular elephant community, headed by proud
grandmother Banna.
</P>
<P>
Three generations -- a rare sight in zoos -- are living in
perfect harmony in the city zoo, to the delight of visitors.
</P>
<P>
It all started in 1972 when the oldest female Asian elephant,
Banna was captured using anaesthesia in Xishuangbanna, Yunnan
Province. She was given a new home in Shanghai Zoo.
</P>
<P>
Later a male elephant Bamo, now turned 31, was transferred to
the zoo from Beijing to act as her mate.
</P>
<P>
Banna gave birth to their first baby, a female, in 1978. Every
four years after that the two elephants watched the patter of
not-so-tiny feet as more offspring arrived. The latest, the sixth,
made her entrance early this year.
</P>
<P>
Last year their second daughter gave birth to a baby elephant.
</P>
<P>
Experts said a three-generation elephant family is a rare sight
in zoos and offers a promising way of saving the endangered Asian
elephants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
