<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Inflation to Stay Higher Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Mew Zealand's Inflation rate
will stay higher than expected in the next three quarters, the
Reserve Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
In its biannual monetary statement, the bank said inflation
will not fall below its target of two percent before the second
quarter next year.
</P>
<P>
It forecast that the underlying inflation, which excludes the
effect of changes in interest rates and one-off price shocks, will
peak at a higher-than-expected 2.6 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
Under New Zealand's law, the Reserve Bank has the
responsibility to keep the country's inflation rate between zero
and two percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank's latest predictions will dash the hopes of some
economists and exporters, who fear efforts to control inflation by
keeping the exchange rate and interest rates high will choke off
economic growth and exports.
</P>
<P>
But Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash said economic figures are
still showing a strong growth, despite some evidence of lower
business and consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
He said the bank's efforts will feed through into next year's
inflation figures, with little or no effect this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
