<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Figures Reveal Dramatic Changes in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Since the mid-80s, China's
largest city has torn down two chimneys a week in its downtown
areas, and it has built 1,000 high-rises, about two thirds of the
existing ones.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10 years, Shanghai pulled down more than 1,000
chimneys in order to protect the city's environment and make room
for more high-rises, which now total 1,523.
</P>
<P>
A local resident said that since the chimneys have been removed
from the downtown areas and with the mushrooming of high-rises,
the living environment there is much better than before.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of the existing high-rises are residential
apartments, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
An official with the local environmental protection department
said that this change proves that construction in the name of
economic progress does not always damage the environment.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since the removal of the 1,000 downtown
chimneys, the city has been free from 108 million cubic meters of
waste gas and 14 tons of soot every day.
</P>
<P>
This has not sapped the vitality of the local industry, the
official said, adding that the city's gross industrial output
value jumped to 525.3 billion yuan in 1995, compared to 82.9
billion yuan in 1985.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of real estate, commercial, trade and
financial projects have been launched on the sites where the
chimneys were located, which gives a strong push to the tertiary
industry.
</P>
<P>
The tertiary industry accounted for 40.1 percent of the city's
gross domestic product (GDP) in 1995, up from 30.8 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Wang Sanqian, research centre director under the Shanghai
Planning Commission, said that over the next 15 years two-thirds
of the factories in downtown Shanghai will either be removed to
suburban areas or be turned to tertiary industries on their
original sites.
</P>
<P>
By then, local tertiary industry is expected to account for
60-65 percent in the city's GDP, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai built 219 high-rises in 1995, and more than 200 new
ones will be put into use this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
