<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet to Eradicate Iodine Deficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A massive drive targeting iodine
deficiency will be started by medics and local governments in the
Tibet Autonomous Region, which has vowed to wipe out disease
related to this by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is a high-risk area because the average content of iodine
in drinking water there is almost zero. The regional government
therefore worked out a series of disease-prevention measures, such
as the use of iodized salt, tea and oral tablets.
</P>
<P>
Tibet will publish regulations on iodized salt supplies, and
will launch an over-all examination of salt products on the
market. Substandard salt will be removed from the shelves.
</P>
<P>
All restaurants and canteens, especially those in schools, have
been urged to use iodized salt, while four processing plants that
add iodine to salt will be built in Tibet and go into production
next year.
</P>
<P>
Iodine will also be added to brick tea, a popular drink for
Tibetans, to give them enough iodine in their daily diet.
</P>
<P>
Iodine-rich pills have been introduced to 60 percent of Tibet
areas as a way to prevent deficiency diseases, and local medics
plan to expand use of the pills in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
