<HEADLINE> Political Forces Oppose Star TV's Entry Into India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- India's political parties have
expressed their opposition to the proposed move by the government
to extend uplinking facility from India to Mogul Rupert Murdoch's
Star TV, press reports said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party asked Prime Minister Deve Gowda to clarify
his stand on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"We stand by Jawaharlal Nehru's 1955 statement that foreign
media should not be allowed entry into India. It poses a threat to
our national security and sovereignty," Congress spokesman V.N.
Gadgil told The Times of India here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The P.V. Narasimha Rao government had turned down a similar
proposal for extending uplinking facility to foreign media
organizations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy General Secretary of the Communist Party of India (CPI)
A.B. Bardhan said that the move "poses a great danger since it
will eventually impinge on our sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
The main opposition party, the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP),
viewed the development as serious and urged the government "not to
throw national security to the winds."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Star TV's Mumbai-based managing director Gene
Swinstead denied rumors that his company was moving its
headquarters to India from Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
