<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christopher: US Not to Cut Forces in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States would not
reduce its armed forces stationed in the Gulf region,
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said Christopher, who arrived in
Saudi Arabia Wednesday, made the remarks to reporters while paying
a visit to the scene of the truck explosion which killed at least
19 U.S. soldiers and wounded 386 others.
</P>
<P>
Christopher said his country would not yield to terrorist
threats and would be "very decisive while dealing with such
threats."
</P>
<P>
Christopher was accompanied during his visit to the blast site
by Saudi Foreign Minister Saoud Al-Faisal.
</P>
<P>
Christopher also visited some Saudi hospitals where some of
the injured were admitted for treatment before flying home, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Christopher said he would present a detailed report about the
tragedy when he was back home to Washington.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Saudi Arabia's deputy Defense Minister
Abdelrahman Bin Abdelaziz excluded any impacts of the blast on the
Saudi-US relations.
</P>
<P>
The strong blast took place Tuesday night at a Saudi Defense Ministry
compound housing American military families in the eastern Saudi
city of Dhahran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
