<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada, Italy Coordinate Stance on U.S. Sanction on Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said today he has lined up with his Italian counterpart
on an unpopular U.S. law that sought to punish non-U.S. companies
doing business with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said after their meeting here that he has forged a
common stand on U.S. sanctions with new Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi, whose country holds the rotating EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came before leaders from the Group of Seven most
industrialized countries -- the United States, Japan, Germany,
France, Canada, Britain and Italy -- meet in the French city of
Lyon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said Europeans will tell the U.S. that the sanction
law violates world trade rules and that they will retaliate if it
tries to enforce it. The EU accounts for 45 percent of Cuba's
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Canada, whose trade with Cuba stood at 515 million U.S. dollars
in 1995, has also strongly criticized the sanction law.
</P>
<P>
U.S. congress approved the Helms-Burton bill this year to
tighten economic and trade sanctions against Cuba after it shot
down two U.S. planes reportedly flying over its air space.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said Prodi and he also expressed a common desire to
boost economic relations. In 1995, trade volume between Italy and
Canada was 5 billion Canadian dollars (3.5 billion U.S. dollars),
an increase of 33.5 percent from the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
