<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis:  G-7 Summit Shifts Focus to Terrorism After Bombing  (By Shang Xuqian)  Part 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the world's seven
leading industrialized nations have found a convenient rallying
point for their summit which opens later today in Lyon, France,
after a terrorist bomb attack on a U.S. military air base in Saudi
Arabia Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The significance of the three-day G-7 summit was marred to some
extent by the absence of Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who
canceled his plan at the last minute, preferring to stay at home
to prepare for next week's second-round runoff against communist
leader Gennady Zyuganov in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who had been invited to previous G-7 summits, was
expected to hold bilateral talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton
and attend "seven plus one" discussions on peace in Bosnia and the
Middle East, the situation in Russia and nuclear safety,
environmental protection, the fight against drugs and organized
crime. But Yeltsin has sent Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin in
his place.
</P>
<P>
With the absence of Yeltsin, among other things, the summit
between leaders of the U.S., Canada, Britain, France, Germany,
Japan and Italy, was expected to achieve little.
</P>
<P>
However, tensions are expected between the U.S. and some of
the other G-7 members over its new law punishing foreign companies
trading with and investing in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
There are also differences between the U.S. on the one side and
Japan and Europe on the other over a new global deal on freeing up
the microchip industry.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of the U.S. base in eastern Saudi Arabia has
therefore provided a timely and welcome shift in attention to
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Although the issue was already on the agenda, U.S. President
Bill Clinton said before leaving for the summit, that the fight
against terrorism will be "our first order of business."
</P>
<P>
"Our first order of business will be to focus the strength and
the energy of the G-7 on the continuing fight against terrorism,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States will lead the way and we expect our allies
to walk with us hand in hand," the president said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Quicken Foreign Investment Clearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
decided to abolish the Empowered Committee on Foreign Investment
in a bid to quicken foreign investment clearance, official sources
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The abolition of the Empowered Committee coupled with the
transfer of the Foreign Investment Promotion Board (FIPB) from the
prime minister's office to the Industry Ministry would hasten the
clearance process, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Empowered Committee, chaired by the finance minister and
comprising other ministers concerned, has so far been working as
the final approving authority for foreign investment projects up
to 3,000 million rupees ( 89.55 million US dollars) cleared by
FIPB.
</P>
<P>
Now the power vested in this ministerial panel will rest with
the industry minister.
</P>
<P>
The Industry Ministry is considering a planning commission
proposal to raise the ceiling of foreign equity participation from
the existing 51 percent to a maximum of 74 percent for projects in
the country's high priority industries, the same sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis:  G-7 Summit Shift Focus to Terrorism After Bombing  (By Shang Xuqian)  Part 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Other G-7 leaders echoed Clinton's remarks when responding to
the fuel truck bomb attack Tuesday on a military housing complex
in Dhahran, which killed at least 19 U.S. servicemen stationed
there and injured more than 300.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister John Major described the attack as "an
appalling act, an act of pure evil, for no reason."
</P>
<P>
He also referred to a bomb explosion in downtown Manchester on
June 15, saying that "we have had all too much of this sort of
experience, this unprovoked bomb, the murder of innocent people."
</P>
<P>
Britain has been a target of bomb attacks by the Irish
Republican Army, which is fighting to oust Britain from Northern
Ireland and re-unite the province with the Republic of Ireland in
the south.
</P>
<P>
France, a victim of terrorist attacks by Algerian Islamic
militants, said in a Foreign Ministry statement that "terrorism
should be fought without fail, no matter where it comes from and
who its authors may be."
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said: "Terrorism
cannot be justified for any reason."
</P>
<P>
Germany also showed solidarity with the U.S. over the attack and
expressed condolences to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
The summit is due to consider a package of 40 recommendations to
combat terrorism, organized crime, illegal immigration and drug
trafficking worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The summit will begin this evening local time with a dinner and
a whole day will be devoted to discussions on Friday, with a
foreign ministers meeting and wrap-up news conference on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The seven leaders will issue an economic communique and a
political declaration.
</P>
<P>
The economic discussions will center on the globalization of
the world economy, unemployment and aid for poor nations.
</P>
<P>
The globalization of the world economy, on the one hand, has
helped boost economic liberalization and economic growth but on
the other, poses a threat to those economies that lag behind the
globalization tempo and are unable to face the increasingly fierce
international economic competition.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will discuss the advantages and drawbacks of
economic globalization and ways of effectively curbing the
repercussions of globalization on employment, financial stability,
international trade and aid.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac, who is chairing a G-7
summit for the first time, has also invited U.N. Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali, World Bank President James Wolfensohn,
International Monetary Fund Managing Director Michel Camdessus and
World Trade Organization Director-General Renato Ruggiero to
discuss debt relief, aid and trade, in an acknowledgement that the
seven countries can't fight these problems alone.
</P>
<P>
The political agenda will include discussing ways to speed up
aid for reconstruction in Bosnia, devastated by a
three-and-a-half-year war, and resettling refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 126,000 College Students Become Chinese Communist Party Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Three percent of all college
students in China are members of the Communist Party of China
(CPC).
</P>
<P>
Sources from the State Education Commission (SEC) said that the
CPC has 126,000 college student members, and that many more
applied to join, as the 1,057 colleges and universities across the
country have become dedicated to strengthening Party building in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The rate of student CPC members increased to more than three
percent in 1995 from less than one percent in 1989. The rate among
students seeking master's or doctor's degrees last year was 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
The SEC sources said that Party schools, which have been
established in Chinese colleges and universities, played an
important role in educating Party members, leaders, teachers,
students and those who asked to join the Communist Party about its
belief and practices.
</P>
<P>
Colleges and universities also strengthen ethics education in
order to help students form an ethical perspective on the world,
life and values. CPC members make up 43 percent of all college
instructors in the country.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,600 students from Beijing University, one of
China's most prestigious universities, have applied for CPC
membership. There were 525 new student CPC members in 1995, 214
more than in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Among students from 45 Shanghai-based colleges and
universities, nearly 7,000 are CPC members and another 30,000 have
applied for membership. More than seven percent of all four-year
college students in Shanghai are CPC members, and one out of every
four students dong post-graduate work has joined the Party.
</P>
<P>
Many students in colleges and universities in Shanghai, such as
Shanghai Jiaotong University, Fudan University and Tongji
University, formed groups to study the Party constitution.
</P>
<P>
Some reports from the Chinese media said that the successes
achieved by the Party and government in political and economic
reforms, micro-control of national economy, anti-corruption, and
price control helped colleges students connect their individual
development with the fate and prosperity of the Party and the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijingers to Focus on Heart Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital will launch a
campaign next month to stop the spread of cardiovascular disease,
which accounts for 27 percent of the total number of deaths in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The "Love Your Heart, Protect Your Heart" drive will include a
public awareness campaign, health consultations, and free blood
tests for cholesterol and fat levels, today's "Beijing Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government hopes to teach Beijing residents the
basics of cardiovascular health and inspire healthy living
habits, the report quoted Jin Dapeng, vice-director of the Beijing
Public Health Bureau, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cardiovascular and cerebrovascular illnesses have become the
biggest threat to the health of Beijing residents. Both diseases
kill about 30,000 people in the city each year, Jin said.
</P>
<P>
In some urban districts of Beijing, 20 percent of the residents
suffer from hypertension. And 33.7 percent of people in 15-69 age
group are overweight, which increases the risk of cardiovascular
and cerebrovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
The citywide disease control drive will be funded by World
Bank loans, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
