<HEADLINE> Kuchma Calls for Constitutional Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
today ordered that a nationwide referendum be held on a draft
constitution on September 25, after a fractious parliament was
unable to approve the charter.
</P>
<P>
Dmitro Tabachnik, Director of the Presidential Office, said the
order was signed by Kuchma at the request of the National Security
Council. He said the council believed that any further delay in
the adoption of the constitution threatens the nation's internal
stability and democratic reform.
</P>
<P>
Tabachnik accused some political forces in the Supreme Soviet
(parliament) of having no desire to work constructively and of
refusing to consider the president's proposals.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between Kuchma and Supreme Soviet Chairman
Vladimir Moroz, the draft constitution should have been adopted
before June 8. However, the parliament was still in the process of
the second reading on June 21.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said the right wing in parliament believed an
item-by-item review of the draft constitution in the second
reading was a deliberate delaying tactic of the left wing, who
were waiting for the results of the Russian elections.
</P>
<P>
Before Kuchma signed the order, Moroz warned today that if the
president decided to hold a national referendum, the parliament
would take appropriate measures according to law.
</P>
<P>
Moroz said any decision on a referendum could only be made
jointly by the president and parliament. If the president exceeds
his authority, he said, his act will be blocked by parliament.
</P>
<P>
Moroz said a referendum, far from ending the crisis, "will make
it even deeper." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Accounts of India's Key Accused in Scam Frozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bureau of
Investigation (CBI) of India has frozen the bank accounts of the
key accused Prakash Chandra Yadav in the multi-crore urea scandal.
</P>
<P>
Chandra Yadav, son of former minister Ram Lakhan Yadav, is
understood to have bank accounts in New Delhi, Hyderabad, Bombay
and Calcutta and had more than 100 million rupees ( 2.99 million
US dollars ) as deposits in several banks in the four cities, the
CBI sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign accounts of the key accused are yet to be frozen,
the same sources said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has asked the
directorate of enforcement to probe the scam since a huge amount
of foreign currency is involved in the deal.
</P>
<P>
Sanjeeva Rao, nephew of former prime minister Narasimha Rao, is
reported to have received 2 million dollar kickbacks in the urea
import deal. The CBI has already arrested him and Chandra Yadav
for this reason. Prabhakar Rao, son of former prime minister Rao,
is still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
The entire 39.70 million dollar urea import deal had been paid
in advance in December last year, yet not a gram of the 200,000
tons of urea reached India so far. Under the contract for import
of the urea between National Fertilizers Limited and a Turkish
firm signed on October 31 last year, 75,000 tons of urea was to
arrive by April this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Vows to Attract More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Pavel
Lazarenko said today that his government will continue improving
investment environment in an effort to attract more foreign
capital.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the remarks at an international
conference of private entrepreneurs, now being held in Ukrainian
capital of Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko said that Ukraine needs at least 40 billion
U.S. dollars of funds to get out of the present economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
A large part of the money will have to come from foreign
sources, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko admitted that political upheavals and lack of
legislation have hindered the attraction of foreign investments in
the past three years.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, however, that Ukraine has intensified
legislation this year. A foreign investment law was approved in
March, which was followed by a series of resolutions on the
privatization of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko announced that the government has selected five
state-owned enterprises in metallurgical and automobile industries
for foreign investment, and tender invitations will be issued
soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
