setting a record high at 1,249.15 on June 5, the Nasdaq has fallen
by more than 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
There was little market movement following this morning's
report that factory orders for big-ticket durable goods shot up
3.3 percent to 171.8 billion U.S. dollars in May, the highest
level on record.
</P>
<P>
Some investors considered an increase in orders can lead to
more production and jobs. That could translate into more consumer
demand and spending, spurring inflation. 
