<HEADLINE> Wild Elephants Harass Villagers in West Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Two elephants of a wildlife park
in western Nepal have played havoc with some neighboring villages
in the last two weeks, a source from the affected area said today.
</P>
<P>
The nearly three-meter-tall elephants, of the Chitwan National
Wildlife Park, often came out at early evening and returned to
jungles in the park the next morning after wandering around the
villages overnight and destroying houses, the source said.
</P>
<P>
One man was killed in such an attack two weeks ago and about
100 villagers have lost their homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The pachyderms also ravaged paddy and maize crops and pulled
down cattle sheds at these villages.
</P>
<P>
Local villagers had tried to use 24 domestic elephants to fight
against the two invaders, but the docile elephants were scared
away on seeing their big wild relatives, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The government then sent a team of army soldiers to drive away
the unwelcome elephants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
