<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donations Help Disabled People in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Donations to the China Welfare
Foundation for the Disabled reached 32.15 million yuan (3.87
million US dollars) last year, according to an official's report.
</P>
<P>
More than 27 million yuan (3.2 million US dollars) of the
donations from home and abroad was allocated to local regions and
spent on programs of rehabilitation, education and cultural and
sports activities for China's 60 million disabled people, said
Deng Pufang, chairman of the foundation's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
Deng said 21 percent of the donations came from domestic firms,
social institutions and individuals. Overseas donations amounted
to 25.41 million yuan, or 79 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Deng, also director of the China Disabled Persons' Federation,
expressed his sincere appreciation to all donors at the annual
meeting of the board of the directors of the federation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The donated funds and materials played an important role in
further enhancing the country's work for the benefit of disabled
people in China and helping fulfill the country's goals set for
last year," today's "China Daily" quoted Deng as saying.
</P>
<P>
"China achieved unprecedented progress for disabled people in
the past five years, with the state providing rehabilitation
services to a total of 2.08 million people with disabilities and
improving their physical conditions in various ways," Deng said.
</P>
<P>
The number of special schools was increased by 559 to 1,379
from 1990 to 1995, and special classes by 3,859 to 6,510. Many
disabled children now attend ordinary schools, and their schooling
rate has increased from 20 percent to nearly 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The employment rate for both urban and rural disabled people
has risen from 60 percent to 70 percent, with about one million
disabled people running their own businesses, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest governing body, recently
finished the outline of a project for the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000) to help the country's disabled people participate in
all aspects of social life.
</P>
<P>
According to the outline plan, a further three million disabled
people will receive rehabilitation services, and many more will
gain new opportunities for normal education, technical training
and employment by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
