<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Have Bigger Living Spaces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Beijing residents each have a
living space of 9.02 sq m -- 2.5 sq m more than they had in 1990,
according to recent statistics.
</P>
<P>
The city has emphasized residential construction over the past
few years, said Wang Zongli, director of the Beijing Municipal
Urban and Rural Construction Committee.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1995, the investment in residence construction
accounted for 12 percent of the total of all construction
projects, Wang said. As a result, the living conditions of nearly
700,000 households improved.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, a record 120,000 households in the city could claim
a better living situation.
</P>
<P>
The director said that the municipal government has set aside
special funds to assist low-income families.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the city has sold living spaces to nearly 20,000
poor families at cost prices; half of them were offered houses in
1995.
</P>
<P>
This year, more than 100,000 families are expected to move
into new quarters, including 11,000 poor families, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
By 1997, all families with a per capita living space below four
sq m will have improved living conditions, Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
