<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Mercosur's Expansion Significant (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The signing of a free trade
agreement between the South American Common Market (Mercosur) and
Chile does not mean that Chile will become a full member of the
block, but the move is seen as a part of drive toward Latin
American integration and could pave the way for other countries to
join the union,
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed Tuesday by the presidents of Argentina,
Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay, the four members of Mercosur, and
Chile at the 10th Mercosur summit meeting in San Luis, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The document, which will come into effective on October 1,
1996, establishes a new tariff system and the different norms for
Chile's trade with Mercosur countries.
</P>
<P>
General tariffs will be reduced initially by 40 percent on 90
percent of the products traded bilaterally between Chile and the
four Mercosur countries. Then they will be cut by 6 percent
annually and eliminated entirely by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on the other 10 percent of products disappear
completely in the years 2003, 2005 and 2010 respectively, which
will mark Chile's full entry into Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
The free-trade market to be formed by Mercosur and Chile will
have a combined land area of more than 13 million square
kilometers, a population of 220 million, a gross domestic product
(GDP) of 900 billion dollars, and a foreign trade of 185 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is hammered out after two years of tough
negotiations because proper terms had to be found for the
commercialization of very sensitive products, particularly
agricultural ones.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has taken into consideration the positions and
intetests of all parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossils Found in Australia Rewrites History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The discovery of fossils of the
world's oldest animals on land in eastern Australia has rewritten
the history of life's evolution from ocean to land.
</P>
<P>
At a farm near Rockhampton, a Queensland coastal city 1,150
kilometers north of Sydney, scientists unearthed three fossils of
amphibious creatures that lived 333 million years ago, the
earliest of their kind ever known in the world.
</P>
<P>
This meant that the history of animals with a backbone living
on land might began in the southern hemisphere, or Australia,
rather than in the northern hemisphere, said Tony Thulborn, one of
the paleontologists who unearthed the fossils.
</P>
<P>
Before this, all other fossil evidence of earliest land
creatures had been discovered in North America, Greenland and
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, the Down Under fossils dated back to the lower
Carboniferous period, near the time of 370 million years ago when
the transition from fish to amphibians took place.
</P>
<P>
In a report published in the latest issue of the international
scientific journal Nature, Thulborn of the University of
Queensland and his colleagues said the three Australian amphibians
were each the oldest known example of their type found anywhere in
the world. Two of them had never been found outside North America
or Europe.
</P>
<P>
When fully grown, the amphibians reached one meter in length.
They had strong tails, a massive head with lots of nasty teeth and
four feeble legs with separate figures and toes, Thulborn said.
</P>
<P>
"They were tied largely to water for reproduction and would
have tadpoles with external gills," he told the Sydney Morning
Herald.
</P>
<P>
One of the three amphibians belongs to a group called
anthracosaurs, which were ancestors of reptiles, birds, mammals
and people.
</P>
<P>
Scientists are trying to unearth more fossils from deeper rock
layers on the site in Rockhampton.
</P>
<P>
"As yet we don't have enough material to know what exactly what
we've got, so we can't answer how this transition (from fish to
amphibians) happened. We might not ever get it, but now we have a
chance," amphibian expert Anne Warren said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Passes Church Arson Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday voted
98-0 to approve its version of a bill aimed at Stiffening
penalties on arson fires at nearly 40 predominantly black churches
across the South over the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The bill, sponsored by Senators Ted Kennedy, Democrat from
Massachusetts, and Lauch Faircloth, Republican of North Carolina,
is designed to raise federal penalties for church arson, and
grants local as well as federal law enforcement agencies extended
powers to track down and prosecute arsonists.
</P>
<P>
"This wave of arsons, primarily directed at African American
churches, is a reminder of some of the darkest moments in our
history, when African Americans were mired in a quicksand of
racial injustice." Kennedy said. "We need to do all we can
together to combat this shameful epidemic and bring the
perpetrators to justice."
</P>
<P>
The Senate's Church Arson Protection Act raises federal
penalties for those convicted of church arson from 10 to 20 years
imprisonment, and broadens the statute of limitations for such
crimes from five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
The bill also authorizes funds to the Justice and Treasury
Departments for additional investigators, and for programs to
train local law enforcement agencies in arson prevention and
investigative procedures.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bill would allow the Department of Housing and
Urban Development to set up a low-interest loan program for the
reconstruction of churches whose congregations could not afford to
insure their property.
</P>
<P>
The House bill, which was approved 422-0 last week, strips
federal regulations that call for the involvement of federal law
enforcement agencies in the investigations of such attacks only if
it has been proved perpetrators crossed state lines to commit
their crime.
</P>
<P>
Both chambers will now go to conference to craft a compromise
between the two bills.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, President Bill Clinton told the leaders of
several religious denominations at a prayer breakfast that the
Federal Emergency Management Agency will make available to
churches arson prevention workshops and other resources.
</P>
<P>
The president also met with a group of leaders of major
national fire and emergency services organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
