<HEADLINE> Karadzic Agrees to Resign, Not Run in Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic will not run in the country's elections on September 14
and has agreed to resign as "president" after the poll, but only
on certain conditions, a senior Bosnian Serb official said today.
</P>
<P>
"In agreement with the Bosnian Serb leadership and due to the
horrible pressures by the international community and the
Yugoslavia, Karadzic decided not to take part in the elections,"
Bosnian Serb Prime Minister Gojko Klickovic told reporters in
Banja Luka in northwestern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic's decision is conditional on a guarantee by the
international community to recognize the self-declared Republika
Srpska, the Serb entity in Bosnia, as a state with full
sovereignty within Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He is also demanding that the international arbitrators
deciding the fate of the northern town of Brcko guarantee to give
the town to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Brcko, a port town linking the Bosnian Serbs' eastern and
western territories, is currently held by the Serbs who see it as
vital for their strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
Although Karadzic says he will not run in the elections, he
will stay as head of his ruling Serb Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Under last November's Dayton peace accord which ended the
nearly four-year war in Bosnia, Karadzic cannot hold office as he
has been indicted by the International War Crimes Tribunal in the
Hague as a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic's offer to resign was made under mounting pressure
from the international community and Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic, who believe his continued presence in office is a
threat to the Bosnian peace process and the post-war nation-wide
elections in September.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the international community's High Representative
in Bosnia Carl Bildt threatened renewed sanctions against the
Bosnian Serbs unless Karadzic quit, following on from Milosevic's
strongly-worded ultimatum on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic's conditions for resigning were rejected by Bildt. He
said the only acceptable condition was that the Bosnian Serbs
abide by the Dayton peace accord which states that indicted war
criminals must quit office and go on trial at the U.N. war crimes
tribunal in The Hague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
