<HEADLINE> Indonesian Defense Minister Urges PDI Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense and Security
Minister Edi Sudradjat appealed to the bickering factions of the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) to unite for the good of the
nation and the party, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"If there are two camps claiming the party's leadership, they
should meet. They are part of the same family after all," the
minister told reporters after a hearing of the house of
representatives' Commission on Security on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The PDI's leadership is split into two factions: one under
Soerjadi which was formed at a rebel congress held from June 20 to
22 in Medan, capital of north Sumatra province. It has the support
of the government and the military; the other faction is headed by
Megawati Soekarnoputri, daughter of late president Soekarno. It
relies on the support of loyal party members.
</P>
<P>
After receiving official recognition as the PDI's leader,
Soerjadi wants to regain control of its headquarters in central
Jakarta. the office is occupied and guarded around-the-clock by
hundreds of Megawati supporters.
</P>
<P>
Soerjadi said he would wait for all 39 members of the Central
Executive Board, who were elected at the Medan congress, to arrive
before he would decide when to take the office.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces have promised to help Soerjadi take the
headquarters if asked, but police said yesterday they had not
received any request for assistance.
</P>
<P>
Anti-riot police have been stationed around the PDI
headquarters to maintain peace and order.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Alexander Litaay, secretary-general of the Megawati
faction's board, said yesterday that his camp had no intention of
giving up the headquarters, maintaining that Megawati had the
legal right to leadership.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Ministry of Home Affairs to undertake an
independent inquiry into the legality of last week's congress.
</P>
<P>
Megawati has also announced she intends to sue minister of home
affairs and the national police chief for allowing the congress to
proceed. A separate suit against the rebel PDI members who
organized the congress is also planned, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has three parties, namely the United Development
Party (PPP), the Indonesia Democratic Party (PDI) and one
functional group (the Ruling Golkar).  
</P>
</TEXT>
