<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Beers Raised Highly Into China Market (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Most of the major foreign beers
have bubbled into China's beer market in a bid to win a big share
in the world's second largest market.
</P>
<P>
Foreign beer brands can now be seen everywhere in cities and
large towns, from the country's north to south, in shop windows,
restaurants, and hotels. Some of them are even served at the
dining tables of well off farmers in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
Most Chinese customers know that the country's best known beer
until the late 1980s was Tsingdao Beer from Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Foreign beer makers started to explore the Chinese market in
the early 1990s, and it took no more than six years for about 30
overseas beer brands to open-up China's market, including the
world's top 10 beer makers.
</P>
<P>
The first overseas beer brand to enter the China market was the
Philippines' San Miguel. The company leased the Guangzhou Beer
Plant and started producing San Miguel-brand beer, in order to get
access into Guangdong's market.
</P>
<P>
Around 50 joint ventures have been set up over the past few
years, involving 500 million US dollars in overseas investments.
</P>
<P>
In the northeastern part of China, top British brewer Bass has
invested 40 million pounds in a local brewing joint venture. The
company has strived to sell British-flavor beer to the generous
northeastern Chinese.
</P>
<P>
And in north China's port city Tianjin, Australian Fosters
purchased the Tianjin Bohai Brewing Company, and started exploring
the local market.
</P>
<P>
Up to now Chinese people have been quite familiar with most
world beer brands, such as Beckers, Budweiser, Bass and Fosters.
</P>
<P>
The American Miller's cooperation with the Five Stars Group in
Beijing is considered as one of the biggest joint ventures that
have been set up in China.
</P>
<P>
Miller invested 100 million US dollars in the venture, which
will raise its annual production capacity to 200,000 tons this
year. The venture is expected to control 20 percent of the
Capital's sales.
</P>
<P>
Another US brewing giant, Anheuser-Busch, is planning to
increase its investment in the Tsingdao Brewing Company to 200
million US dollars, in order to hold 20 percent of the Chinese
company's total shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Beers Raised Highly Into China Market (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After entering the China market, the next job for the foreign
brands is to encourage Chinese people to buy their products, and
drink them. What seems to be one of the keys to this thirst for
sales is advertising.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said foreign beer brands have fought an "Ads
War" against the Chinese breweries through TV, newspaper, and
radio promotions.
</P>
<P>
Most cash-starved Chinese breweries lost their upper-hand in
their monopolies of local markets in the beer stakes, and also
lost their brands, after having established joint ventures with
foreign investors, one industry source said.
</P>
<P>
However a spokesman for Australian Fosters, which has several
joint ventures in China, had to confess that his company will not
be able to make profits until the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Most foreign beer producers hope to elbow into the local market
first, where their ventures are sited, without learning what the
whole China market is really like.
</P>
<P>
And the China market is really too big for them, economic
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
However not all Chinese will become potential customers of
foreign brand beers, after they find the beer's prices are three
times that of the domestically-made beers, a hotel manager said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign brands have pinned their hopes on the expanding of
the China market, expecting that their products might become the
favorite alcoholic beverages of the growing number of middle-class
Chinese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Beers Raised Highly Into China Market (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Per capita beer consumption in China was just 12 liters last
year, just one eighth of that of the average American
drinker. Chinese people are expected to drink more than 30 million
tons of beer by the year of 2000, making China become the world's
biggest beer market -- and a liquid gold market for brewers.
</P>
<P>
This has brought to the top of agenda just how to develop and
protect China's national beer-making industry, while continuing
with the opening-up policy, an economist said.
</P>
<P>
China has about 860 brewery plants, but less than 60 plants
have an annual production capacity above 50,000 tons each. And
about 40 percent of the breweries could not make profits.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately some back-bone enterprises of China's brewing
industry have made substantial progress in strengthening their
positions in China's own market over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Chinese brands have made successes in their own bids
to explore world markets.
</P>
<P>
Two big brewing companies have got themselves into shape,
namely, Tsingdao Beer Brewing Company, which controls 2.4 percent
of China's beer market, and the Zhujiang Brewing Company, which
plays a leading role in the south of China.
</P>
<P>
Yanjing Brewing Company, headquartered in Beijing, has also
become the country's biggest beer-maker, after it merged with
Huasi Brewing Group. The company has formed an annual capacity of
500,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
However only time can tell who will win in the fierce
competition in China's beer market. It might be the Chinese
customers, drinking as much as they can, who are the victors in
the battle for keeping the beer taps flowing in the world's second
biggest drinks market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
