<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal City Makes Painstaking Efforts to Keep Sky Blue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Blue skies over Weihai city, a
coastal city in east China's Shandong Province, has become one of
its boasts - thanks to an all-out attack on air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The city's environmental department has ensured that
construction plans are mapped out to prevent the creation of new
pollution sources.
</P>
<P>
So far 57 boilers, fueled by coal, have been converted to burn
cleaner oil or liquified gas. Regular inspections are also carried
out of existing polluting sources.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the 1980s the city began to step up efforts to
improve urban heat supply facilities and promote cleaner
fuel. Over the past few years more than 70 million yuan has been
spent on building two thermal power plants and 42 centralised heat
supply stations. The environmental department has also spent two
million yuan building an automobile monitoring facility to check
vehicle exhaustion pollution.
</P>
<P>
The city's clean environment has helped draw investment from
both in and outside China. An electronic industry park funded by
the Ministry of Electronic Industry has taken shape. And a number
of foreign-funded enterprises in electronics, medicine, food,
biological engineering and fine chemicals, which require high air
quality, have also sprung up in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
