<HEADLINE> Pirated Electronic Materials Destroyed in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 48,000 pirated and
illegal audio and video tapes and CDs have been publicly destroyed
by the Guangzhou Customs Office.
</P>
<P>
They were confiscated during a recent run of raids and
inspections by officials in south China's Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
Most of factories producing electronic publications are
concentrated in the area. But officials have also made great
progress in eliminating piracy of video and audio material.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that 457 inspections were conducted in the
province between last September and March of this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 134,000 illegal publications were confiscated, while
1,000 units were suppressed and 1,500 were ordered to stop
business for overhauling.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has also paid great attention to
strengthening its control over trademark, patent and copyright
goods.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, six markets and four underground production
lines in the province, which sold or created illegal electronic
products, have recently been closed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
