<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Year of "Zero Population Growth" for Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 26 (Xinhua) -- With the number of deaths exceeding
that of births, Italy experienced the third year in a row of the
so-called "zero population growth" in 1995.
</P>
<P>
There were 526,064 births, compared with 555,203 deaths, in the
country in 1995, according to an annual population report released
by the government's Institute of Statistics today.
</P>
<P>
Only because of an influx of immigrants, Italy's population
increased 55,000 in the year to a total of 57,333,996.
</P>
<P>
Italy entered into "zero population growth" for the first time
in 1993, as it was turning increasingly into a country of
one-child families.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend in average family size, main due to
financial constraints, since has continued to keep Italy's birth
rate among the lowest in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Head of U.S. Southern Command in Panama Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 26 (Xinhua) -- General Wesley K. Clark
replaced Barry R. McCaffrey today as the command-in-chief of the
U.S. Southern Command which has its headquarters in Panama.
</P>
<P>
John Shalikashvili, chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff,
presided over the ceremony of Clark's replacement.
</P>
<P>
Shalikashvili took the Southern Command standard from the hands
of acting Chief Rear-Admiral James B. Perkins III and handed it
over to General Clark.
</P>
<P>
General Clark replaced retired General McCaffrey who left
Panama on March 4 for Washington to take over the post of director
of the Office of the National Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton recommended Clark for the post of
the commander-in-chief of the Southern Command on April 18 and the
U.S. senate approved it on June 20.
</P>
<P>
Clark has served as director of strategy, plans and policy for
the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff since April 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Command is the U.S. army division for military
operations and coordinations in Latin American and the Caribbean
countries, except Mexico. The Southern Command with 770 officers
will move its headquarters to Miami in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Born in Chicago on December 23, 1944 and a graduate of the West
Point Military Academy in the United States, Clark was named a
second lieutenant of the army in the armored division in 1966.
</P>
<P>
He studied at the University of Oxford in Britain where he
obtained a Master degree in philosophy, politics and economics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
