<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Calls for Britain's Constructive Stance on Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin today
urged Britain to take a realistic and constructive position and
cooperate with China on the issue of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with El Pais, one of the most
influential newspapers in Spain, the Chinese president, who is
paying a state visit to Spain, said that all issues concerning
Hong Kong's transition period must be discussed and agreed between
the Chinese and British sides in line with the Sino-British Joint
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will return to China's sovereignty on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Any unilateral action to make substantial changes of the
current political system in Hong Kong without an agreement between
the two sides runs counter to the joint declaration, the principle
of dovetailing with the Basic Law and related agreements and the
understandings reached between China and Britain," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"There is only a year left before China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong, so I hope the British side will take a
realistic and constructive stance and strengthen cooperation with
the Chinese side," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the Chinese government, after resuming the exercise
of sovereignty over Hong Kong, will pursue the policies of "one
country, two systems", "Hong Kong ruled by Hong Kong people" and
"high-degree autonomy" in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will strictly abide by the Basic Law and
guarantee law and order and long-term prosperity and stability in
Hong Kong, Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang arrived in Madrid on Monday for a four-day state visit to
Spain. He will leave for Oslo, Norway, on Thursday to continue his
six-nation European and central Asian tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Calls for Firm Global Cooperation Against Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo today called on all nations to promote international
cooperation in combating drugs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of the International Day of the War
Against Drugs, Zedillo said that the war against drugs should
begin in the consuming countries with firm international
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the producing and consuming nations and those who
serve as transit points or money-laundering centers should take
their responsibility in the task.
</P>
<P>
"We Mexicans recognize that we are victims, never the
benefactors of the trafficking of illegal drugs," he said. The
best way to combat the drugs is to prevent it, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He urged every nation, community, family, school and every
citizen to assume that attitude.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo also signed an agreement for coordination between the
chambers of deputies and the senate and the federal
Attorney-General's Office in the prevention, control and combat of
drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
