<HEADLINE>   Paraguayan President, General Responsible for Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Paraguayan President Juan
Carlos Wasmosy and retired General Lino Cesar Oviedo were jointly
responsible for the institutional crisis in April, a two-chamber
investigation committee (CBI) said today.
</P>
<P>
In a report sent today to Judge Alcides Corbeta who is in
charge of investigating the cause of the crisis, the CBI said that
both the president and the former army chief General Oviedo
violated the national constitution by committing different crimes
that the justice authorities are investigating.
</P>
<P>
The CBI accused Oviedo of insubordination and sedition for
refusing President Wasmosy's order to have him relieved as army
chief and for attempting to stage a coup.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CBI investigation concluded that President
Wasmosy violated the constitution and laws through "actions or
omissions" as commander-in-chief of the armed forces and as the
person wielding executive power.
</P>
<P>
The committee stressed that Wasmosy announced General Oviedo's
refusal to obey orders on April 22 but did not order an immediate
disciplinary arrest of the military officer.
</P>
<P>
The CBI also criticized Wasmosy for offering the Defence
Ministry to Oviedo and described the President's embrace of the
military leader during a transfer of command ceremony in the army
as "inexplicable".
</P>
<P>
General Oviedo is now in prison under preventive detention for
alleged contempt and attempted sedition against the constitutional
order.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 social organizations continue to promote a campaign
asking for a political trial of President Wasmosy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia Coach Resignation a "joke" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The president of the Croatian
football federation Nadan Vidosevic said Wednesday in Zagreb that
the resignation of national coach Miroslav Blazevic announced
Monday was just a "joke".
</P>
<P>
Vidosevid explained that was due to the reception the coach
received on his return from England. "It was not official," he
said.
</P>
<P>
When Blazevic arrived back at Zagreb airport after Sunday's 2-1
defeat by Germany, he was greeted by some 2,000 whistling fans
who vented their anger at his decision to rest several stars
prior to a group defeat by Portugal.
</P>
<P>
That result meant that the Croats as group runners-up had to
face Germany in their quarter-final rather than the relative
"minnow" Czech Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
