<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suzhou's Local Economic Development Zone Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Suzhou, an economic powerhouse in
east China's Jiangsu Province, has put a local regulation on
economic development zones into effect to provide standardization.
</P>
<P>
The city is now home to five state-level development zones and,
by the end of 1995, there were already ten province-level
development zones there; they covered an area of 81.24 sq km and
involved 2.2 billion yuan in investment in basic construction; 566
enterprises have gone into operation in the development zones and
have provided 640 million yuan in profits and taxes.
</P>
<P>
The regulation is aimed at solving problems that have cropped
up in developing the zones, such as management and organization,
overall planning, and collecting and managing development funds.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, the overall planning of the
development zones must be included in the region's overall
economic and social development program, and state-controlled
professional fund management will be set up in the zones.
</P>
<P>
The regulation is expected to accelerate the construction of
development zones, experts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
