<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Men's Gymnastic Squad Expected Better Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. men's Olympic gymnastics
coaches have high expectations about the selected team at the
trials beginning Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the 1995 World Championships in Japan, the U.S. men
plummeted from third place after the compulsories to ninth after
the optionals, nearly failing to qualify for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
U.S. coaches promised the Olympic squad will be more
consistent and choose routines with difficulty equal to that of
any team in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"You can't go in there with 9.6, 9.7 start values and expect
to beat teams with 9.8., 9.9 start values," said U.S. men's
Olympic coach Peter Korman.
</P>
<P>
Leading contenders for the U.S. Olympic squad include reigning
national champion Blaine Wilson and four-time national champion
John Roethlisberger, who finished second to Wilson this year.
</P>
<P>
Seven athletes will make the Olympic squad, chosen by a
combination of all-around scores at nationals and trials. The
national championships score counts 40 percent, while trials
count for for 60 percent in the selection process.
</P>
<P>
Korman considered the Chinese were pretty strong while the
Russians might be slightly favoured for second. "After that,
everybody is practically even." 
</P>
</TEXT>
