<HEADLINE>   Experts Debate Poverty in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Some 270 million people in Latin
America live below the poverty line and 350 million lack any kind
of social security, Antonio Colomer, president of
the Spanish Council of Ibero-American Studies, said today.
</P>
<P>
There are also 150 million illiterate people in the region and
a shortage of some 100 million low-income houses. Sixty percent of
the region's economically active population work in the black
economy, Colomer declared in the first European Congress of Latin
American specialists.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 800 delegates from 40 countries have come together to
discuss the problems faced by Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
