<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 26 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Salaries Drop
</P>
<P>
Argentines were paid an average monthly salary of 854.2 pesos
(about the same amount of U.S. dollars) in March, down 1.7 percent
over last year, the Economy Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Salaries have been shrinking since the beginning of the year,
averaging 931 pesos in January and dropping to 874 pesos in
February.
</P>
<P>
Industrial Output Goes Up
</P>
<P>
The industrial output for May gained by 5.4 percent compared
with April and by 1.7 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
But the Latin American Economic Research Foundation said the
increase was due solely to the fact that the month had more
working days.
</P>
<P>
Bank Deposits Reach Nearly 50 Billion Dollars
</P>
<P>
Deposits in Argentina's banks rose to 49.511 billion pesos in
May, up 10 percent over the end of 1994, when the Mexican
financial crisis swept Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
Of the total deposits, 52 percent correspond to foreign
currency deposits and the remainder to peso deposits, said
"Adeba," a financial body which groups the national capital banks
except Citibank.
</P>
<P>
First Quarter Investments Drop
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic investment dropped by 14 percent in the first
quarter of this year compared with the same period of last year,
the Economy Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The most serious investment decreases were observed in the
automobile industry with 23.6 percent, transportation equipment
industry with 17.9 percent, construction industry with 17
percent and machinery with 10.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The drop in investments, implying inactive economic activities,
responded to a 3.2 percent decrease in the gross domestic
product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Arrives in Lyon for G-7 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton arrived
in the southeastern French city of Lyon today for a summit of the
Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized nations, which is to open
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton reportedly said before leaving the White House that the
fight against terrorism has become the "first order of our
business."
</P>
<P>
A fuel truck bomb attack Tuesday on a military housing complex
in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, claimed at least 19 lives of the
U.S. servicemen stationed there.
</P>
<P>
"Our first order of business will be to focus the strength and
the energy of the G-7 on the continuing fight against terrorism,"
said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Defeating these organized forces of destruction is one of the
most important challenges our country faces at the end of this
century and at the beginning of the next," the president added.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism, which has already been on the agenda of the
three-day summit, is expected to be given more attention as other
leaders of the seven countries echoed Clinton's remarks.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister John Major described Tuesday's bomb
attack as "an appalling act, an act of pure evil, for no reason."
</P>
<P>
He also referred to a bomb explosion in downtown Manchester on
June 15, saying that "we have had all too much of this sort of
experience, this unprovoked bomb, the murder of innocent people."
</P>
<P>
Britain has been a target of bomb attacks of the Irish
Republican Army, the military wing of the breakaway Sinn Fein
Party of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
France, who had been victim of terrorist attacks of Algerian
Islamic militants, said in a Foreign Ministry statement that
"terrorism should be fought without fail, on matter where it comes
and who its authors may be."
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said: "Terrorism
cannot be justified for any reason."
</P>
<P>
Germany also showed solidarity with the U.S. in the attack and
expressed condolences to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
The summit was expected to put forward 40 recommendations on
the fight against organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
The weight of the summit, however, was lessened by the absence
of Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who decided not to turn up so
as to gather strength for a runoff with communist leader Gennady
Zyuganov in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 was made up of the United States, Britain, France,
Canada, Germany, Japan and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seles Knocked out of Wimbledon Tennis Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, ENGLAND, June 26 (Xinhua/OANA) -- The world joint
number one tennis player Monica Seles of the United States was
defeated by unseeded Slovak player Katarina Studenikova in the
second round of the on-going 1996 Wimbledon Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
Seles, who has won every Grand Slam title but Wimbledon,
produced an uncharacterically error-ridden game and was finally
knocked out of the Championships by 5-7, 7-5, 4-6.
</P>
<P>
It was the earliest ever defeat in a Grand Slam event for the
talented young tennic super-star, who had missed the last three
Wimbledon Championships after being injured by a spectator in
Hamburg in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Seles, the second seed in the Championships, was not in her
aggressive form and was really at a loss against her Slovak
opponent, who ranked 59th in the world.
</P>
<P>
"I am not too happy with the way I am playing but I still just
have to reassess. She played smarter than I did today," Seles said
after the match.
</P>
<P>
The women's fourth seed Arantza Sanchez Vicario and fifth
seeded Anke Huber trashed their opponents in straight sets and
entered the next round of the Wimbledon women's singles events.
</P>
<P>
In the man's singles clashes today, second seeded German
tennis ace Boris Becker survived an early scare before easing to
victory over Spanish player Thomas Carbonnel in the second round
of the fortnight Championships.
</P>
<P>
Becker, who looked to be going to be another upset after
losing the first set, pulled himself together and fought back to
win 4-6, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
The German player said after the game that "I really have to
play my best tennis in the second set in order to get back into
the match"
</P>
<P>
"I have to really take control at the beginning of the
match. I can not give away a set like I did today. In the next
round, I have to start better," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nine seed Thmoas Enqvist of Sweden joined the lower-half
casualties when he lost to American Malivai Washington in straight
sets, 4-6, 6-7, 3-6.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Centre Court program begins with an eagerly
awaited rematch between defending Champion Pete Sampras and Mark
Phipippinssis, the man who beat him in the Australian Open earlier
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
