<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karpov, Kamsky Adjournments in 11th Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Anatoly Karpov and Gata Kamsky
adjourned play after six hours Wednesday in Elista, Russia in the
11th game of their World Chess Championship match.
</P>
<P>
Karpov, the defending World Chess Federation champion from
Russia, leads 6.5 points against 3.5.
</P>
<P>
The first player to reach 10.5 points chalks up the title and
gets 937,500 U.S. dollars while the loser gets 562,500. A victory
is worth one point and a draw half a point.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-born Kamsky, who lives in New York, chose a Slav
Defense with the black pieces. He sealed his 59th move when the
six-hour time limit was reached, forcing adjournment until
Thursday. Each player has a rook and two pawns to back his king.
</P>
<P>
The championship is being held in Elista, capital of the
southern Russian republic of Kalmykia, where FIDE president Kirsan
Ilyumzhinov is the regional leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
