<HEADLINE> McCormack Wants 2002 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Management Group
will bid one billion U.S. dollars for the commercial rights to
soccer's 2002 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
In an interview, IMG chairman and chief executive Mark
McCormack indicated that negotiations with soccer's world
governing body FIFA had already begun.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said that he could do "a tremendous job for the
World Cup", but he also added that whether they get the chance was
going to "depend on a lot of factors.
</P>
<P>
The 2002 World Cup is being jointly staged by Japan and South
Korea. Receiving the commercial rights to the event could mean
everything from the recruitment of sponsors to the negotiation of
TV rights. 
</P>
