<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Soccer Clubs Receive Cash from UEFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- European soccer governing body UEFA
has paid 190 million Swiss francs (about 150 million U.S. dollars)
from Champions' League revenue to the participating clubs and
soccer federations, according to a statement received on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two finalists took the biggest portion, with winner
Juventus of Italy receiving 18.150 million Swiss francs and
runner-up Ajax Amsterdam, 16.8 million, followed by Borussia
Dortmund with 13.325 million though the German club was knocked
out in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
The amounts were collected from starting money, prize money and
TV rights. 30.220 million francs were distributed among the 49
member associations.
</P>
<P>
UEFA also announced that Germany will have only three
guaranteed spots in the 1997-98 UEFA Cup.
</P>
<P>
Only Italy, France and Spain, who top the ranking list, will
have four. 
</P>
</TEXT>
