<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, Czech Republic to Clash for Euro Soccer Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua/OANA) -- European soccer giant Germany
and unfancied Czech Republic defeated their strong opponents
England and France by the same score 6-5 in two thrilling
semi-final shoot-outs today and they will compete for the European
Soccer Championships honour on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Host team England, which in shocking prime form since the
beginnig of the tournament, started today's game brilliantly with
the two-minute goal from top striker Alan Shearer.
</P>
<P>
The German side, which had to fight without its super-star
Klingsmann, tried hard to resist the waves of fierce attacks from
the England side and hit a great equalizer by Stefan Kuntz at the
15th minute.
</P>
<P>
Under the deafening cheering roars of thousands of home fans,
confident England players nealy dominnated all the stages of the
game, but failed to get another goal.
</P>
<P>
At the extra-time play, both sides displayed inspiring
attacking football and got some golden chances to get a so-called
"golden goal", but the 30-minute play still ended with 1-1.
</P>
<P>
In the thrilling shoot-outs, Gareth Southgate, the bright young
England player, was the unlucky man as he stepped up with the
shoot-out locked at 5-5 after some brilliant spot-kicks.
</P>
<P>
In another semi-final clash between favourite France and
so-called out-sider Czech Republic played in Manchester city, the
Czech team, which defeated favourite Italy and Portugal earlier in
this Championships, produced another big surprise by ousting the
current hottest candidate to win the Euro soccer title.
</P>
<P>
French team, full of well-known soccer stars, failed to
displayed their excellent team work and was at some time of the
game playing above their normal level.
</P>
<P>
In the identical shoot-out after 0-0 draw, French player Pedros
saw his spot-kick saved by Czech goalkeeper, sending the
star-studded French team crashing out of the Championships.
</P>
<P>
The lucky German and Czech teams, removing their last hurdles,
are heading for European Soccer Championships final to be played
at the Wemblely Stadium on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
