<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Airport Traffic up 8 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Passenger traffic at airports
worldwide grew by a healthy 8 percent in the first quarter of 1996
over the same period last year, according to the latest figures.
</P>
<P>
Cargo volume handled at the world's airports grew by a modest 3
percent, said the monthly airport traffic report to be published
Thursday by the Geneva-based Airports Council International (ACI).
</P>
<P>
The report, based on data from 460 airports worldwide, shows
that Africa had the biggest growth in passenger traffic, up 12
percent, followed by a 9 percent increase in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The growth in Europe was partly due to heavy Easter traffic,
promotional fare packages by several carriers and extra capacity
created by new entrants in Spain, Italy and Britain, said Maria
Hinayon, ACI's manager in charge of data processing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
