<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opposes Hegemonism, Power Politics: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
reiterated here today that China will never seek hegemonism and
will never become a superpower.
</P>
<P>
"We resolutely oppose hegemonism and power politics in any
form," Jiang said during an interview with the Spanish newspaper
El Pais (The Country).
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president arrived here Monday on a four-day state
visit to Spain at the invitation of King Juan Carlos I.
</P>
<P>
In the interview today, Jiang said that even if China's
comprehensive national strength becomes much stronger in the
future, it will adhere unremittingly to the principles of mutual
respect for sovereignty and territorial integrity, non-aggression,
non-interference in each other's internal affairs, equality and
mutual benefit, and peaceful coexistence.
</P>
<P>
"We will make efforts, on the basis of these principles, to
maintain and develop friendly and cooperative relations with other
countries, including the U.S., Russia and Japan," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the Nansha Islands in the South China Sea,
Jiang said that China has indisputable sovereignty over the Nansha
islands and nearby water areas.
</P>
<P>
It was not until the 1970s that some littoral countries began
to make territorial claims over the Nansha islands, Jiang pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
"We hold that disputes can be settled through peaceful
negotiations, and if conditions for talks are not ready, we can
shelve disputes and carry out joint development," he said.
</P>
<P>
With the joint efforts of China and countries concerned in
recent years, the situations in the South China Sea have been
comparatively stable and there is no such problem as dangerous
situations.
</P>
<P>
Spain is the first leg of Jiang's six European and central
Asian nation tour, which will also take him to Norway, Romania,
Uzbekistan, Kyrghyzstan and Kazakhstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
