<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises Help to Prevent Church Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today promised federal help to prevent church arsons at a White
House prayer breakfast he hosted for religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Emergency Management Agency will make available to
churches arson prevention workshops and other resources to help
them stem the recent rash of fires aimed mostly at predominantly
black churches, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, before departing on a scheduled trip to France for the
G-7 summit, also met at the White House with a group of leaders of
major national fire and emergency services organizations.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 religious leaders from various denominations were
present at the prayer breakfast.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 40 suspicious fires have struck churches, mostly with
predominantly black congregations in the South, over the past 18
months.
</P>
<P>
As part of the FEMA's response outlined today to the church
leaders, the agency has provided 773,000 dollars to the affected
states for arson training programs, will distribute radio and
television advertisements describing arson prevention tips, and
has established a toll-free number as a central clearing house for
information on arson prevention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
