<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFOR to Play Supporting Role in Mostar Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSTAR, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The NATO-led Implementation Force
(IFOR) will only play a supporting role in securing the upcoming
Mostar elections, an IFOR commander said today.
</P>
<P>
"There must be no misunderstanding: the ballot of June 30 is
neither organized nor controlled by the (IFOR) military," General
Xavier de Lambert, commander of the IFOR division in southeastern
Bosnia, told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said that "it is definitely the role of the local police to
ensure that all voters can freely vote" under the supervision of
the UN international police and the European Union Administration
in Mostar.
</P>
<P>
The EU has organized the municipal elections in Mostar with the
aim of unifying the ethnically divided city.
</P>
<P>
Muslims and Croats fought fiercely in Mostar in the 1993-94
period and each has since taken over roughly half of the city.
According the rules of elections, many people have to cross into
the territory of the former enemies to cast their votes, giving
rise to concerns that violence might flare up on the election day.
</P>
<P>
Lambert said the IFOR will gather around 2,500 troops in Mostar
on the election day as a backup for the UN and EU police, but
"this force would only intervene upon request from Mr. Perez
Casado," who is the EU Mostar administrator.
</P>
<P>
The French general said that the IFOR in Mostar will be "a
visible presence that will not however turn the city into a
fortified camp." 
</P>
</TEXT>
