<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Damage Mounting in Every Sphere: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The failure of solidarity, vision
and responsibility causes environmental damage to mount in every
sphere of the world.
</P>
<P>
The world faces a linked crisis of the environment, quality of
life and population, according to a report released here today by
the Independent Commission on Population and Quality of Life.
</P>
<P>
The global population is currently adding 88 million every
year, and environmental damage is mounting in every sphere, the
report warned.
</P>
<P>
In the developed countries, they face unemployment, economic
insecurity, family breakdown, rising crime, and the crisis of the
welfare state, it said.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, despite its rapid economic growth, poverty is proving
stubbornly persistent almost everywhere. One to two billion people
are still denied their most basic rights to a basic, acceptable
quality of life. Some 800 million are malnourished, 1,300 million
have no access to clean water, 900 million adults are illiterate
and more than 400 million children are denied education, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
It also pointed out that internationally, programs to eradicate
poverty or to combat environmental problems lack adequate funding,
while national policies give priority to economic targets
disregarding quality of life.
</P>
<P>
If the above mentioned trend is not quickly reversed, the
report foresaw such a world picture: the planet is heading by the
middle of the next century for a population of perhaps 11 billion
with environmental problems at crisis level, and poverty and
social division rampant.
</P>
<P>
The commission presented a challenging set of concrete
proposals for a radical shift of direction:
</P>
<P>
-- Placing sustainable quality of policymaking;
</P>
<P>
-- Accelerating progress towards stabilizing the world's
population by massive efforts in health, education and the use of
development assistance;
</P>
<P>
-- Raising poor, marginal and excluded groups to a minimum
standard within two decades;
</P>
<P>
-- Establishing new patterns of production and consumption, and
encouraging new lifestyles in the context of a globalized economy
and rapid technological progress;
</P>
<P>
-- Fostering a new sense of mutual responsibility, guided by
care; and
</P>
<P>
-- Changing present patterns of governance, nationally and
internationally, so as to overcome deadlocks in the international
order.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Commission on Population and Quality of Life,
which was set up in 1993, consists of seven Western governments,
three international agencies (the UN Population Fund, the
International Planned Parenthood Federation, and the World Bank),
and five major private foundations (Ford, Rockefeller, MacArthur,
Hewlett and Mellon). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960627.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The West Criticized for Imposing Reforms on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador to Kenya
Chen Pengchu today criticized the western countries to force
developing countries to implement unrealistic economic and
political reforms.
</P>
<P>
Chem Pengchu said developing countries should be given time to
adopt new and realistic measures.
</P>
<P>
Chen Pingchu, who is on a working tour to Nyanza Province,
western Kenya, was conferring with Nyanza Provincial
Commissioner (PC) Joseph Kaguthi in Kisumu today.
</P>
<P>
He said China has defied pressure from the west and is
committed to undertaking reforms at its own pace.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ambassador expressed concern with the widening
gap of trade between the countries, saying that China's exports
to Kenya last year totaled 76.4 million Pounds Sterling as
compared with Kenya's exports to China valued at 2.12 million
Pounds Sterling only.
</P>
<P>
In reply, the PC said lack of flow of trade information was
the main hindrance to improving the trade between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He thanked China for its role in developing rural areas of
Kenya and said that the two countries have a lot to learn from
each other since they both faced similar challenges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
