<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Looted Goods on Sale in Monrovia Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Selling of looted goods has become
widespread in Liberia's devastated capital, Monrovia, even as
normalcy returns to the city following the recent factional
fighting and looting.
</P>
<P>
An investigative report reaching here today said computers,
television and radio sets, eletronic gadgets and parts of
cannibalised vehicles are on sale in the markets, a scene that
was never seen in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Bags, medicines and others, looted from the United Nations
agencies in the city, are also being peddled in the streets.
</P>
<P>
One of the Liberian carpet traders was quoted by the report as
saying that he got his supplies from ''some of the fighters."
</P>
<P>
The goods were being sold cheaply with a fairly new color
20-inch tv set going for 100 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another said he together with many other traders, preferred to
sell to members of the African peacekeeping forces, the ECOMOG,
because ''they have U.S. dollars to buy''.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior army officer from Nigeria, who is currently
serving with the ECOMOG, denied that most of the goods were being
bought by the peacekeeping soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He said that traders from other west African countries had not
stopped travelling to Monrovia in spite of the war.
</P>
<P>
The report also said the street fighting, which started on
April 6, had left Monrovia devastated with many houses,
government offices and other structures completely destroyed.
</P>
<P>
While some of the buildings were damaged by rockets, others
were wilfully burnt down after everything in them had been looted
by fighters belonging to the various warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out in the Liberian capital once again among
the warring factions in April after the dismissal of ULIMO-J
leader Roosevelt Johnson from the government and attempts to
arrest him on murder charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
